commit_message:
Do not name variables as builtins

We should not name anything as a reserved word or builtin where it is
possible. This is the HACKING policy in some of the other projects.

Change-Id: I51978839c107a077701f57d05489c32c6ee84cc7

commit_message:
port test_extensions into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I071c4e6ff3d36d4cbfe7a7a27885ddf013a52b8c

commit_message:
Use six.string_type instead of basestring

This patch replaces basestring with six.string_type.
Let our code don't break in Python3 environment.
See http://pythonhosted.org/six/#six.string_types

Change-Id: Ib0c74b1f2a90dbee9ce56be01ebac51bbe8dc468

commit_message:
port test_services into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Id38c7fd4bae451c2489385e485e637f31ccfb481

commit_message:
Replace qpid_host with qpid_hostname

This patch replaces `qpid_host` with `qpid_hostname` in both the
documentation and the config file sample. `qpid_host` has been shipped
as the parameter to specify qpid's hostname, although the correct one is
`qpid_hostname`.

DocImpact
Closes-bug 1242715

Change-Id: I25f2d0e505560e1762f7f059728c33c47a23439e
(cherry picked from commit 21ea5f6535dd484fa7934d07f3519fbda7e5f6ee)

commit_message:
LxcProvider refactoring

Move prepare_host method from LxcProvider to LxcContainer.
Also make code some more clean.

Added configure_container.sh script which make initial
configuration within container.

Removed LxcProviderStaticIpTestCase. Now all provider's code
is covered in LxcProviderTestCase.

blueprint multihost-deploy

Change-Id: Icfe483d61deeadf3afae2eef2b74cdb1770c2a70

commit_message:
Change "project" to "project_id" in cloudpipe-create

The CLI was stating that the name of the project should be used, but the
parameter needs to be the project_id.

Change-Id: If0908a1b72c526f6436432ff18599423f89f7d1f

commit_message:
Test image member is enforced

* Testing is an image member able to get the image
* Testing the image is invisible for not member tenants
* Moving negative tests into a new file
* Using uuid for random ids

Change-Id: I7f9550b3b9ff30fbcd73b4817ab0a0f20689e7c0

commit_message:
Flatten hypervisor-show dictionary for printing

Flatten the nested dicts so that hypervisor information can be more
easily used at the command line.

Change-Id: I5dfcf9d10f917a63bde09f0b5a691784a5e8f02b
Closes-bug: #1243512

commit_message:
Adds basic plumbing for RESTful API service

This patch adds some basic plumbing for a Solum RESTful
API service. It uses the excellent and simple Falcon library
as its WSGI pipeline processing and route handling. Included
is a simple VersionsResource and a few serialization helpers
along with tests that cover all of the added code. Hoping that
this patch will spark some discussions around how to approach
building the API service.

addresses blueprint rest-api-base

Change-Id: I7c8f62f09d1555b4375abad049055ae0f2658169

commit_message:
Remove nose from requirements list

This commit removes nose from the requirements list. The issues with
python 2.6 and testr should go away if we move to using unittest2
instead of unittest. So there is no reason to use nose ever!!

Change-Id: I08de2a42e04b91531d6bfef8c3600a98a760c77a

commit_message:
Make vm cleaner script more flexible

Adds a few options to vm_vdi_cleaner to make it
more flexible.
-Divide orphans into types "deleting" and "zombie"
 *deleting refers to instances stuck in task_state "deleting" and
  vm_state "active"
 *zombies refer to instances that are deleted but are running on
  the HV
-Allow shutting down orphaned instances as an option other than delete

Change-Id: Ie8599d05313e7853c8fe99fda72a54d14b897d65

commit_message:
feat(controller) : Implement Queue Controller

This patchset contributes a queue controller for Marconi client.
Allows getting messages, claiming messages, updating claims & releasing
them as well returning queue names and metadata.

Change-Id: I5ad6972d9f6419800df6f8bd8713e80cf64438a2
Implements: blueprint queues-management

commit_message:
Remove the use of common.uuidutils.gen_uuid

There's a movement to remove gen_uuid from the
openstack common.  This change removes it's use
from Cinder and just puts the call inline.

Change-Id: I07329bab9553e15e498ddbda3848d50b8f48fd53

* Debian/Ubuntu don't use chkconfig

commit_message:
Install Guide: make sure that the admin can use the nova command

The first nova command example might be executed on a compute node by
the user, and it's likely that python-novaclient has not been installed
there. Suggest to the user to log on the controller or to install the
client.

Change-Id: I57009deb4a817966f9a37036f3230a418a5133e3
Partial-Bug: #1245946
backport: havana

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-13 20:55:13.000000000', 'message': 'Ensure autoscaling actions occur for percentage adjustment

Fixes bug 1251007

Previously if the AdjustmentType was set to PercentChangeInCapacity,
then depending on the choice of the instance group MinSize and the
scale-up policy ScalingAdjustment, no autoscaling actions may occur
even when the under-scaled alarm fires.

This situation occurred if:

   (MinSize * ScalingAdjustment / 100.0) < 1.0

in which case the group never get gets scaled up even if the under-
scaled alarm stays in the alarm state forever.

Now we follow the rounding rules used by AWS Autoscaling:

  http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/as-scale-based-on-demand.html

Change-Id: I79e5e743de1944ace5ef2c4dbcb76c9cab7262bb
'}]
commit_message:
Ensure autoscaling actions occur for percentage adjustment

Fixes bug 1251007

Previously if the AdjustmentType was set to PercentChangeInCapacity,
then depending on the choice of the instance group MinSize and the
scale-up policy ScalingAdjustment, no autoscaling actions may occur
even when the under-scaled alarm fires.

This situation occurred if:

   (MinSize * ScalingAdjustment / 100.0) < 1.0

in which case the group never get gets scaled up even if the under-
scaled alarm stays in the alarm state forever.

Now we follow the rounding rules used by AWS Autoscaling:

  http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AutoScaling/latest/DeveloperGuide/as-scale-based-on-demand.html

Change-Id: I79e5e743de1944ace5ef2c4dbcb76c9cab7262bb

commit_message:
Update install.sh to reflect recent oslo.db format

The previous sql_connection option has been deprecated and replaced
with the database.connection option in oslo:

[database]
connection = mysql://heat:heat@localhost/heat

The old option still works, but the default is only respected from
the new option, which is confusing if you're relying on the previous
behavior where specifying nothing got you the sql_connection default.
So update the installed config to remove the deprecated options.

Change-Id: I0f5b4587358ec99b47c8ab3ee924191bbf2760a2
Closes-Bug: #1241826

This CR contains timing/profiling utils addition and their usage. Why not just separate them to two commits? It's a really tiny patch but let's practise the approach of separating everything to one feature per CR. Initially my comment about separating was because lack of the patching vanilla plugin with commit message "A timing/profiling utility for savanna", so, this CR has at least incorrect commit message. CRs separation is the common practise in OpenStack and in any other open source projects, it helps reviewers make their work better and help patches to be landed earlier. You want to land your patches as fast as possible and so the write way for you is to separate them to small straightforward patches. In addition it'll be much easier to rebase such small CRs.

Some useful links to read:

* https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages

commit_message:
A timing/profiling utility for savanna

Created a simple function decorator that allows for the given
function to be timed.  This will facilitate some profiling work
with the aim of improving the performance of plugins.

Implements blueprint simple-timing-profiling-utility

Change-Id: Ib5a85b053a6a09fbf5d2dd1fefe8a8163c5b18e5

commit_message:
Move tests into ceilometer module

Doing this allow for potential importing of the tests and is cleaner
than having a side directory. Nova already does this, so let's move.

Change-Id: I77fc9c5356f3962363fd355b8dbf44fbeec157ee

[{'created': '2013-11-13 02:32:44.000000000', 'message': "Fix server update attribute test

This is testing if an attribute not in the update_allowed_keys
results in UpdateReplace. Whilst this is true here, it's using
an attribute that is not a valid resource attribute. The only
valid resource attributes that I know of are:
(Properties, Metadata, UpdatePolicy, DeletionPolicy)

Just want to make sure we are testing the right thing.

Change-Id: Ic84239b0ff3960968293c2c367971f30d091e833
"}]
commit_message:
Fix server update attribute test

This is testing if an attribute not in the update_allowed_keys
results in UpdateReplace. Whilst this is true here, it's using
an attribute that is not a valid resource attribute. The only
valid resource attributes that I know of are:
(Properties, Metadata, UpdatePolicy, DeletionPolicy)

Just want to make sure we are testing the right thing.

Change-Id: Ic84239b0ff3960968293c2c367971f30d091e833

commit_message:
Modifies CLI to show nodes by instance uuid

This patch updates the node-show subcommand for ironic so that it
shows the node that matches the given instance UUID.
ironic node-show [--instance] id
It also updates node-list subcommand so that it can show all the
nodes that have instance UUID associated or the opposite.
ironic node-list [--associated true|false]
This patch also fixes a few strings for i18n support.

Change-Id: I2aec9ba6e296e0d1db9f3ef9eed7236ecfb32cf6
Closes-Bug: #1239026

commit_message:
[bp] Add support for Cinder multi-backend

* Create class cinder::backend.
   Sets DEFAULT/enabled_backends

* Create define cinder::type.
   multip-purpose function to create type and optionally set extened
   information.

* Create define cinder::type_set.
   multi-purpose set function to set extended information.

* Copy rbd, iscsi, and nfs volume providers to support multi-backend
   Now provided as cinder::backend::<driver> to ensure that multi-backend
   aware resource is|[ not] used.

* Add rspec for new parts to ensure expected function.

Blueprint: cinder-volume-multi-backend

Change-Id: I6df9cadaad3b9ce2ab4b0e87dba9b5056459db10

[{'created': '2013-11-12 17:13:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add a specialized Event Type model and db table

it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the

retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema

monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

SELECT id, desc FROM event_type;

monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

commit_message:
Add a specialized Event Type model and db table

As the events API gets fleshed out and more robust,
it will become increasingly necessary to ensure that the
database schema modeling events has the ability to quickly
retrieve a list of event types. With the current schema
having a foreign key from event to unique_name (the
monolithic generic string key lookup table), in order to
get a simple list of event types, one needs to do the following:

SELECT DISTINCT e.unique_name FROM event;

Not only is this inefficient, but the readability of the
model and database schema suffers from the generalization of
the unique name field relationship. With this patch, a new
event_type table is added to the schema to allow for quick
and easy lookups of event types like so:

SELECT id, desc FROM event_type;

This will lead to future ability to categorize
event types with ease. Instead of adding columns to the
monolithic unique_name table, we would only need to add a foreign
key relationship to the new event_type table tying the event_type
to a future event_type_class table...

Note: this is a resubmittal of an earlier patch from Jay Pipes
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41316/)

Change-Id: Ia57c2425d2431cea41c71904cb1d3511a4633aa8
Partial-Bug: 1211015

commit_message:
"instance_usage_audit Hhour"->"instance_usage_audit_period hour"

In Point-2, change the command "openstack-config --set /etc/
nova/nova.conf DEFAULT instance_usage_audit Hhour" to
"openstack-config --set /etc/nova/nova.conf DEFAULT
instance_usage_audit_period hour"

The description about editing the
/etc/nova/nova.conf [DEFAULT] section has already been added by
someone else.

Change-Id: I978790c6a6c8d9a122ac972c6d3758a694645290
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1249779
(cherry picked from commit 69a73be10399e47b75d594f541b94ac433603201)

Actually create $BASE/new dir and set perms.

Need to run with root privs to create dirs under /opt. Then chown the
new dir under /opt to jenkins:jenkins so that the jenkins user can write
to that dir.

Change-Id: I1f3bc2226b0965a0d530a7a6070bdad5e0d84618

users avoid argparse nargs='*' problems.

'trove create <name> <flavor_id> --databases <db_name>'

commit_message:
Usage String has Positionals after Optionals

print positionals before optionals in the usage string to help
users avoid argparse nargs='*' problems.

ex: 'trove create --databases <db_name> <name> <flavor_id>'
fails with 'error: too few arguments', but this succeeds:
'trove create <name> <flavor_id> --databases <db_name>'

Change-Id: I400c9f0ca5580bd287c5f3bcf935352e88071bc8
Closes-Bug: #1243981

commit_message:
Don't use deprecated module commands

The commands module was deprecated since version 2.6 and it has been
removed in Python 3. Use the subprocess module instead.
See http://docs.python.org/2/library/commands#module-commands

Closes-Bug: #1248216
Change-Id: I4091179c6b312ae8534b30adc518eff67d68320a

Given there already changes to check based on guest tools version, I'm happy to use the values that are proposed here - although there is confusion about exactly when the device_id should be set to 0002.

Just to be clear, it should be set to 0002 if the new style tools are installed.  This is independent of the hypervisor version, and as I mentioned inline XenServer 6.1 ships with both old and new style tools (for different versions of Windows).

commit_message:
Xenapi: Allow windows builds with xentools 6.1 and 6.2

Building a windows VM with pre-installed xentools
6.1 or 6.2 requires device_id to be set on XEN VM record.

Requires xenapi_device_id to be set on the
image metadata, which is then used to set the device_id
on the vm record.

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint allow-windows-builds-with-xentools6-1-and-6-2
Change-Id: Id3cd9d569519f2df1afa046ddabf33f00d63c615

commit_message:
trigger devstack-gate test as early as possible

if we have changes to devstack-gate we need need to run this as
early as possible. So do this the second we've decided that
we need to run devstack gate in our project list.

Change-Id: I60464965a2e4cea5e1c85ea8833e98a8471fa5f1

commit_message:
Extract git_fetch_at_ref

The really dense logic in the zuulification of trees is actually
hard to understand. Extracting it into a common function makes
this much easier to understand the AND and OR logic of it.

Change-Id: I96f94da8901cd94772d1910d39b48270a45f73e6

commit_message:
disable novnc service to get gate to pass

Trove does not use this service in trove so it should not cause an
issue if we disable it.

Change-Id: I9b808c69a162e350f93be7bff3176efb4b654c89

commit_message:
Add received reviews to review stats

Add a new column that shows how many reviews each person received in the
same time frame.  It also shows the ratio between reviews given and
received.

As a side effect, the result now also includes those that submitted
patches but did no reviews.  I think that's still useful information to
show when looking at the heath of the review queue.

Change-Id: I936c65c91a76c3de6872da0f53a1fa10e3ca111e

commit_message:
Supports get node by instance uuid in API

The API needs to expose a means to search for a node, given an
instance uuid. This patch supports getting a node by an instance
uuid (/nodes?instance_uuid=<xxx>), getting all the nodes that have
instance uuid associated (/nodes?associated=True)

commit_message:
RFC: Make _ more explicit by importing it

Some static analysis tools and new developers have trouble with the
magic __builtins__ method for accessing '_'.

Change-Id: I570021ec72b217e7cc3d1d65734a61adc096eba8

FWIW, I think my vote is that this sort of thing is fine to squash into the original change and update it for the original reviewer.

One possible downside is that if someone is new to git/gerrit/openstack development, they may misunderstand what happened, and end up pushing again, erasing your updates by accident.

So, I guess I would only do it as the last step before approving it, which seems like the case here.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-13 11:59:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

Style tweaks for Id3cd9d569519f2df1afa046ddabf33f00d63c615

Id3cd9d569519f2df1afa046ddabf33f00d63c615 looked good to me,

and a doc comment which was more of a NOTE than a doc comment.

code review.

commit_message:
Removed unused methods from db.api

Since 406ff304bb09f144a59448e0e9d2d01160c7d553 reservation methods
is not called directly so it can be removed from the public API

Related to blueprint db-cleanup

Change-Id: I5a62d0528705b6773f8667375b4e8e3922a1bd15

commit_message:
Discrepancy between README.rst and nova help

1) --version in README should be --os-compute-api-version

2) NOVA_URL should be OS_AUTH_URL

Change-Id: Ib8989e6923e2073bcc31d2a17d346eb436effdc8
Closes-Bug: 1250842

commit_message:
Remove skips for bug 1182384

Commit a2ccca0 fixed some negative tests to check for neutron when
determining the invalid ID to use for nova APIs that behave differently
when using neutron vs nova-network.

This patch uses the same idea to remove the skips in place for bug
1182384 in the compute security group negative tests.

Closes-Bug: #1182384

Change-Id: I58ba125012a74ea49311a163e9bf7fd7af33c1fc

There is no image api in nova v3 api. so move the tests
that just test glance into glance testing from nova v3
testing. The rest tests in compute.v3.image.test_images

commit_message:
move nova v3 delete image tests into glance testing

There is no image api in nova v3 api. so move the tests
that just test glance into glance testing from nova v3
testing. The rest tests in compute.v3.image.test_images
just are the tests related to nova, like creating image
from a server. Also move the negative tests in test_image
to a separate file.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I42c0f08434de4a51d41f2fafd95cfaf72a9dd6da

Remove unused code in api/compute/admin/test_quotas.py

commit_message:
Bump SWIFT_LOOPBACK_DISK_SIZE_DEFAULT over swift max_file_size

Swift is returning 50x error codes because its disk is too small, set
size bigger then max_file_size in an attempt to fix the problem, or at
least reduce it.

"we create a 4GB device, but swift thinks it can write 5GB, hence fail"
--sdague

This patch based off of Iccd6368e4df71abb5ccfe7d361c64d86e1071d35

Change-Id: Ib56a98cd74e7edf1fa90facc25c72632d43180f1

commit_message:
Removes generate_uuid from uuidutils

As discussed at the summit, generating the UUID string seems
trivial enough to not need a function. Each project should define
its uuid generation helper function according to its required format.

Change-Id: I2689a5d810e1b7663bc6b77385b2913844c70b9e

I think the point of pull-tools is that it can be used at any time to get the latest checkouts, not just at the very beginning of a devtest run.  This would undo the changes to elements/seed-stack-config/config.json and we'd need to tell people to reapply them.

I think that's why the git pull --ff-only was added.  We can't reasonably handle every failed merge, and it's probably best to just let the user figure it out if something goes wrong.

For local changes such as these, we could try a "git stash save" first, then pull, then "git stash pop", but I'm not very keen on that either.  I'd rather just have pull-tools bail out and tell the user they need to look into what went wrong.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-11-13 20:03:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This isn't going to help me as is because I modify the 'power_manager' as well. Ideally we'd come up with a better bootstrapping mechanism for the seed VM to avoid having to edit this file at all.

Until we do so my preference it to just manually resolve these differences myself. Anything clever here is likely going to accidentally blow away modifications to someone's config.json."}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-11-13 20:57:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

Point taken.'}]

commit_message:
Revert changes before pulling repository

When running devstest.sh multiples times, it fails due to
changes in the config.json file made by devstest_seed.sh
script.

Reverting this changes before updating the repo, will allow
to rerun the devtest.sh script.

Change-Id: Ia0af95d51c0f0ddd66fa7324e7ea784cf3a6e6ce

Seems sort of stupid to me; why would I want EIO to mean not-a-mount-point? What about EPERM; that shouldn't indicate not-a-mount-point.

On the other hand, it does match Python stdlib, and our ismount() is intended to be a more-efficient version of stdlib's, so I guess we should do as stdlib does.

http://hg.python.org/releasing/3.3.3/file/6e81c3a16d1c/Lib/posixpath.py#l211

Call this a very reluctant +2 from me."}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2013-11-13 03:14:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

Thanks Sam.

I have another question on following lines, although those are not relative with this patch. I just don't understand it."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-13 04:43:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Sam, I believe the stdlib's behavior is a disservice, as it hides errors from mounted file systems.

I purposely did not model ismount exactly because of that. See the dialog in the referenced bug.

But neither will I officially block this patch from going forward."}, {'account_id': 6198, 'date': '2013-11-13 04:59:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2013-11-13 06:13:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@peter

Thanks for your answer for inode question.

For the patch itself, I am hesitant. I know handling it is much better then hiding it. Let's wait for others'response"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-11-13 06:53:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I didn't notice the loss of the lstat efficiency; sorry about that.

Not performing superfluous lstat() calls is of high importance, so that aspect of this change can't be merged.

I think the change to catching all OSErrors is tolerable, though. There's really three cases here: (a) yes, this is a mount point, (b) no, this is not a mount point, and (c) an error occurred and I have no idea if this is a mount point or not. Refusing requests to drives that are throwing up wacky errors seems like a reasonable thing to do; it just means the proxy gets a 507 instead of a 500.

I agree that it confuses the semantics of utils.ismount() a little, but I don't think the users of utils.ismount() care all that much. (FWIW, only the backend HTTP servers use utils.ismount(); all the other daemons use os.path.ismount() for reasons unknown to me.)"}, {'account_id': 6835, 'date': '2013-11-13 11:24:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-13 12:22:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

[{'created': '2013-11-12 09:26:33.000000000', 'message': 'catch all OSError and return False in utils.ismount

User maybe face the errno.EIO when calling utils.ismount. The reason is
codes only catch errno.ENOENT and re-raise others. But in newer python
os.path.ismount implementation(http://paste.openstack.org/show/51930/),
codes catch all. So this patch catch all OSError and return False.

Change-Id: I5d9018f580181e618a3fa072b7a760d41795d8eb
Closes-Bug: #1249181
'}, {'created': '2013-11-13 11:24:27.000000000', 'message': "catch OSError to prevent breaking request /recon/diskusage

commit_message:
catch OSError to prevent breaking request /recon/diskusage

swift.common.utils.ismount maybe raise some OSError in some special
cases; and the request against /recon/diskusage doesn't handle it
before. This patch let output of mounted keyword is the error's message.

Change-Id: I5d9018f580181e618a3fa072b7a760d41795d8eb
Closes-Bug: #1249181

Hi,
It is not clear to me why the information needs to be stored in the database. Metrics will need to be updated at every interval and this seems like a huge burden on the database. It is not clear to me why we do not maintain this data in memory - for example by storing the data in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/scheduler/host_manager.py#L95?
Thanks
Gary"}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-05 07:00:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

@garyk

There were some discussions about fanout vs. DB in scheduler sub-meeting and ML previously.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/scheduler/2013/scheduler.2013-07-23-15.00.log.html

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-June/010485.html

Basically at the current stage, they prefer to use DB method for stats, instead of fanout.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-08-05 08:20:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

@Shae: This is what was written: "I believe it's things that change very rarely so an alternative can be to only send fanout messages when capabilities change!" If I understand correctly the metrics will be updated at every interval. This could be a huge hit on the database - say we have 1000 hosts - this will mean 1000 updates at every interval. Can the database deal with this every second? I do not think so.
Thanks
gary'}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-05 08:43:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

@garyk

This patch doesn't bring additional update times onto the database. We reuse the periodical task update_available_resource() in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35767/. That is: without our patch, if we already have 1000 updates at every periodical task interval, the database is dealing with this every interval in the current code."}, {'account_id': 4458, 'date': '2013-08-05 08:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

@Boris Pavlovic

We have measured the time for nova scheduler to get all compute nodes by compute_node_get_all() while compute nodes are being updated in the meanwhile. Here is what we did:

The total number of compute nodes in DB is 10K.

We used 500 processes on 4 servers to update compute nodes, each process updates 5 different compute nodes in 12 seconds.

Case1:
1) We use the current DB schema. Suppose the number of key-value pairs in 'cpu_info' is S.
And there is no record in compute_node_stats. (i.e. no join pain).

If S = 20, the time to for nova scheduler to get all nodes by compute_node_get_all() is 1.830127 seconds.
If S = 40, the time is 1.884750 seconds.

2) Then we add one more column 'metrics' in compute_nodes.
If S = 20, the time is 2.157449.
If S = 40, the time is 2.41351.

That means in the above case (no JOIN) one more column 'metrics' brings 15%~28% performance drop as the number of key-value pairs in each compute node varies from 20 to 40. However the total absolute time is 1~2 seconds, which is acceptable I think.

Case2:
If each compute node has several records in compute_node_stats. The situation is different.

1) We use the current DB schema. And if the record number of compute_node_stats for each compute node is 20, and the number of key-value pairs in 'cpu_info' is also 20, the time is 19.007912 seconds.
If the number of compute_node_stats for each compute node is 40 and the number of key-value pairs in 'cpu_info' is also 40, the time is 36.161468 seconds

2) Now we add one column 'metrics' in compute_nodes, the above times become 19.810151 and 38.036670 seconds respectively. In the above case, the performance drop we bring is 4.2% to 5.2% as the number of stats for each node varies from 20 to 40.

Do you think that makes any sense?"}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2013-08-14 09:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

2) Then we add one more column 'metrics' in compute_nodes. If S = 20, the time is 2.157449. If S = 40, the time is 2.41351.
That means in the above case (no JOIN) one more column 'metrics' brings 15%~28% performance drop as the number of key-value pairs in each compute node varies from 20 to 40. However the total absolute time is 1~2 seconds, which is acceptable I think.
Case2: If each compute node has several records in compute_node_stats. The situation is different.
1) We use the current DB schema. And if the record number of compute_node_stats for each compute node is 20, and the number of key-value pairs in 'cpu_info' is also 20, the time is 19.007912 seconds. If the number of compute_node_stats for each compute node is 40 and the number of key-value pairs in 'cpu_info' is also 40, the time is 36.161468 seconds
2) Now we add one column 'metrics' in compute_nodes, the above times become 19.810151 and 38.036670 seconds respectively. In the above case, the performance drop we bring is 4.2% to 5.2% as the number of stats for each node varies from 20 to 40.


And by the way, I also saw some patches used a similar approach to extend table compute_nodes recently, e.g., https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40764/.

[{'created': '2013-07-05 08:30:31.000000000', 'message': 'Added a new method to store resources in DB

The compute manager uses plugins to get the resource information of each node.
And then sends and stores in DB for the scheduler to read and do scheduling.

The patch adds a table [compute_node_resources] to store the resource data,
and reuses compute_node_update() API to update the information.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and the
blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

'}, {'created': '2013-09-05 02:20:52.000000000', 'message': "Stored metrics into compute_nodes as a json dictionary

The compute manager uses plugins to get the metrics information of each node.
And then sends and stores in DB for the scheduler to read and do scheduling.

The patch reuses table compute_nodes and adds a new TEXT column to store the
metric data as a json dictionary.

The reason that we don't put those metrics into the compute_nodes_stat table
is because of the scale issue of sqlalchemy's joinedload(). For example, for
10K compute nodes with each node has 20 stat records, it takes more than 16
seconds for sqlalchemy to do the query to get all the compute nodes and their
stat information. Adding more stat records into the compute_node_stats table
would make it much worse. The JSON structure in compute_nodes table would
scale much better. And we could re-work the stats table into JSON structure
just like this metrics feature in future patches.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and the
blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

Change-Id: I4d20565567e9907cfcc92b1c1b15f3b35a806797
Signed-off-by: Shane Wang <shane.wang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Stored metrics into compute_nodes as a json dictionary

The compute manager uses plugins to get the metrics information of each node.
And then sends and stores in DB for the scheduler to read and do scheduling.

The patch reuses table compute_nodes and adds a new TEXT column to store the
metric data as a json dictionary.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and the
blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

Change-Id: I4d20565567e9907cfcc92b1c1b15f3b35a806797
Signed-off-by: Shane Wang <shane.wang@intel.com>

commit_message:
Allow spaces in quoted SSH command arguments

The check_ssh_injection() method was rejecting arguments with spaces
even when they were quoted, this was causing problems with some volume
driver commands such as commands for a storage pool with spaces in the
name.

Note that this backport also fixes a typo that has been fixed separately
in master with commit eb0f2e4dd538a79184efbb23d7e404147dfe877b .

Closes-Bug: #1244415
Change-Id: Ie4b809e1b39fdb752cf634e6d3c0a3924d8ac52b
(cherry picked from commit 2737c76cb2fb436f117a4f635aebca7a01691d88)

commit_message:
Shorten physical resource name to custom limit

The default limit for resources is 255, which is
determined by the column size of the name columns in
other openstack project databases.

The limit for nova servers is 53 characters due to typical default
linux HOST_NAME_MAX of 64, minus the '.novalocal' appended to the name.

The reduced name will consist of the following:
* the first 2 characters of the name
* a hyphen
* the end of the name, truncated on the left to bring
  the name length within the limit

The validation fix from bug: #1238272 has been removed.
Closes-Bug: #1250291

Change-Id: Iccaf905b2e73433a671559c49223c2b635402853

commit_message:
Enabled django-compressor for javascript sanity test

By default the test did not run with the compressor on
which did load the javascript. There's no way to test errors
compressing the javascript.

Fix bug #1187576

Change-Id: I1db226ae9709ff818e8d13b7935ded66c0f6eae3

commit_message:
Make file store writes cooperative

The filestore driver does not yield after each chunk
write which means that any other write threads/requests
must wait until the entire image has been written before
being serviced which may cause problems when multiple
requests happen in parallel.

Change-Id: Ib1369e1ad7e42a132822b42c7f886200dc714512
Co-authored-by: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Fixes: bug 1247165

[{'created': '2013-10-28 14:40:03.000000000', 'message': 'Separate a deployment from a benchmark

A deployment was separated from a benchmark on several levels:

-   The Deployment model represents an installation of OpenStack. This
    model is related with the Task model through a many-to-one relation.

-   A set of operations extends the rally.db.api.* to store a deployment
    related data.

-   rally.db.deploy.Deployment is an abstraction of the data relating to
    the deployment.

-   DeployEngine provides an abstraction to manage specific deployment
    engines, control status of a process and handle errors. Very
    closely associated with the Deployment object and in role of a
    context manager controls its status:

        # Create instance of the Deployment
        deployment = rally.db.deploy.Deployment(config={
            "name": "DevstackEngine",
            "provider": {
                "name": "DummyProvider",
                "credentials": ["root@10.2.0.8"]
            }
        })

        # Performe of deployment
        with DeployEngine(deployment) as deploy:
            endpoint = deploy.deploy() #raised an exception

        # If failure occur into context of deploy the status of
        # deployment would be changed to "deploy->failed".

        # If some test broke the deployment e.g.:
        with DeployEngine(deployment) as deploy:
            ...
            tester.benchmark() #raised an exception
        # the status would be changed to "deploy->divergent".

-   The orchestration provides management operations on deployments.

-   Support of deployment commands into CLI.

In the current state CloudConfigManager is used by the BenchmarkEngine
to process a verification and a testing. But the deployment represented
as an endpoint (a set of parameters like username, password, project
and auth_url). The translation function was added to provide backward
compatibility between this formats.

Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

Change-Id: I8da5d6bfd969960ec452256dcf4a3bb21505e537

commit_message:
Separate a deployment from a benchmark

A deployment was separated from a benchmark on several levels:

-   The Deployment model represents an installation of OpenStack. This
    model is related with the Task model through a many-to-one relation.

-   A set of operations extends the rally.db.api.* to store a deployment
    related data.

-   rally.db.deploy.Deployment is an abstraction of the data relating to
    the deployment.

-   EngineFactory provides an abstraction to manage specific deployment
    engines, control status of a process and handle errors. Very
    closely associated with the Deployment object and in role of a
    context manager controls its status:

        # Create instance of the Deployment
        deployment = rally.db.deploy.Deployment(config={
            "name": "DevstackEngine",
            "provider": {
                "name": "DummyProvider",
                "credentials": ["root@10.2.0.8"]
            }
        })

        # Performe of deployment
        with rally.deploy.engine.get_engine(deployment) as deploy:
            endpoint = deploy.deploy() #raised an exception

        # If failure occur into context of deploy the status of
        # deployment would be changed to "deploy->failed".

        # If some test broke the deployment e.g.:
        with rally.deploy.engine.get_engine(deployment) as deploy:
            ...
            tester.benchmark() #raised an exception
        # the status would be changed to "deploy->divergent".

-   The orchestration provides management operations on deployments.

-   Support of deployment commands into CLI.

Implements: blueprint independent-deploy

Change-Id: I8da5d6bfd969960ec452256dcf4a3bb21505e537

commit_message:
Make v3 admin_password parameters consistent

There are API parameters "admin_password" and "admin_pass" on some APIs:
 * AdminPasswordController: admin_password
 * EvacuateController     : admin_password
 * RescueController       : admin_pass
 * ServersController      : admin_pass

These parameters mean the same thing, it is the admin password of a vm
instance. They should be the same parameter name because of the meaning.

DocImpact

Partially implements bp nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I452672e064d0dc4a1d5700bb96c01de8087f33d8

commit_message:
Deal with unicode strings

The ironic client was trying to convert unicode strings received from the
API to ascii causing it to fail, this patch will correct it.

Change-Id: I8765abb188f758f982807a38f5d291fbc2be0da9
Closes-Bug: #1247156

commit_message:
Custom output file on the print_*() functions

In order to make the code more flexible and cleaner when testing (and
debugging) the print_*() functions can now redirect the output to a
different output file.

Change-Id: I34779220d80e037bdfe9e528ffad5187ff109ceb

commit_message:
xenapi: Fix agent update message format

Fix the agent update message send so Windows guests will work

Message must be formatted: "url,md5sum"

Change-Id: I675cc5a7ca522696eab1820c14c48361ff7e0f74
Closes-Bug: 1250165

commit_message:
Do not allow bad keys while updating quota

Raise 400 (bad request) error instead of 200 (ok) if bad keys
are passed to the update quota request

Closes-Bug: #1248815

Change-Id: Iaefaa4961dd3783dfab15f843cbb2dcb12195a7d

Add the semver documentation

This is a fork of the upstream semver documentation with an aim towards
being a PEP440 compliant implementation of the ideas.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-24 19:46:42.000000000', 'message': "Check if dir exists before calling listdir

Changes along the way to how we clean up and detach after
copying an image to a volume exposed a problem in the cleanup
of the brick/initiator routines.

The clean up in the initiator detach was doing a blind listdir
of /dev/disk/by-path, however due to detach and cleanup being
called upon completion of the image download to the volume if
there are no other devices mapped in this directory the directory
is removed.

The result was that even though the create and copy of the image
was succesful, the HostDriver code called os.lisdir on a directory
that doesn't exist any longer and raises an unhandled exception that
cause the taskflow mechanism to mark the volume as failed.

Change-Id: I488755c1a49a77f42efbb58a7a4eb6f4f084df07
Closes-bug: #1243980
(cherry picked from commit 1766a5acc5c948288b4cd81c62d0c1507c55f727)
"}]
commit_message:
Check if dir exists before calling listdir

Changes along the way to how we clean up and detach after
copying an image to a volume exposed a problem in the cleanup
of the brick/initiator routines.

The clean up in the initiator detach was doing a blind listdir
of /dev/disk/by-path, however due to detach and cleanup being
called upon completion of the image download to the volume if
there are no other devices mapped in this directory the directory
is removed.

The result was that even though the create and copy of the image
was succesful, the HostDriver code called os.lisdir on a directory
that doesn't exist any longer and raises an unhandled exception that
cause the taskflow mechanism to mark the volume as failed.

Change-Id: I488755c1a49a77f42efbb58a7a4eb6f4f084df07
Closes-bug: #1243980
(cherry picked from commit 1766a5acc5c948288b4cd81c62d0c1507c55f727)

commit_message:
Increase size of first disk for slave nodes in VirtualBox

When the Ceph role is selected 16GB isn't enough to satisfy
the minimum space requirements for all volume groups.

Change-Id: I24d51c64b183455dceffbf8cb8813395aaf46142
Related-Bug: #1248662

commit_message:
"instance_usage_audit Hhour"->"instance_usage_audit_period hour"

In Point-2, change the command "openstack-config --set /etc/
nova/nova.conf DEFAULT instance_usage_audit Hhour" to
"openstack-config --set /etc/nova/nova.conf DEFAULT
instance_usage_audit_period hour"

The description about editing the
/etc/nova/nova.conf [DEFAULT] section has already been added by
someone else.

Change-Id: I978790c6a6c8d9a122ac972c6d3758a694645290
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1249779

Thin provisioned LV's don't need secure delete to protect
from data leakage.  Also, zeroing these out kinda defeats
the purpose of using thing provisioning.

This patch add a check for the lvm type and if it's thin simply
returns from the lvm.clear_volume() method.

Change-Id: Ie6764209018152565295291efc6fbba553698ae6

commit_message:
Don't zero out thin provisioned LV's on delete

Thin provisioned LV's don't need secure delete to protect
from data leakage.  Also, zeroing these out kinda defeats
the purpose of using thing provisioning.

This patch add a check for the lvm type and if it's thin simply
returns from the lvm.clear_volume() method.

Change-Id: Ie6764209018152565295291efc6fbba553698ae6
Closes-Bug: #1240299
(cherry picked from commit de4392314f9b0def8fab65679ec5668aec98fbee)

commit_message:
Sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible

DocImpact

Change-Id: I19228304dcef8a4f7e6022d97eb652da647df879

commit_message:
Sync iso8601 requirement and fixes test case failures

1. Sync requirements from global Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
2. iso8601>=0.1.7 "parse_date()" could successfully handle date string
which only have date part like YYYY-MM-DD, it caused two Glance test
cases failure.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: I2625eb3888111829a9da4d093b34193b8795f264
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8160ae293383ec600c05fd2e4b38164bca7704c4)
Conflicts:
	glance/tests/unit/v1/test_registry_api.py
	requirements.txt

commit_message:
Fix wrong description when updating quotas

when updating quota for a resource, with 'force_update=false', an
exception will be raised when the new value is less than the used quota
values(used and reserved). This patch changes the description of
exception.

Change-Id: Iede70444341817afb6953eb604fe4de186622916
Closes-bug: #1243062

commit_message:
Increase size of first disk for slave nodes in VirtualBox

When the Ceph role is selected 16GB isn't enough to satisfy
the minimum space requirements for all volume groups.

commit_message:
[REVERT AFTER RELEASE]  HA, Murano and Ceph  disabling

As HA, Murano and Ceph do not work in tech-preview-4.0 version,
we disable them on UI for this techpreview release (grey them out, not remove from UI)

Edited templates

Change-Id: Ib7a85996168b841b1ab51abe149f6416b99d620f
Closes-Bug: "1250373 "

commit_message:
Support volume_readonly_update using XML format

Almost all API support JSON and XML format together,
But this API does not support xml format.
In the request of xml format,
the type of parameter "readonly" in the body is string.
In the request of JSON format,
the type of parameter "readonly" in the body is bool.
But the code only support bool, not support string.
This branch is to solve this problem.

Closes-bug #1244848

Change-Id: I7f2b09a0063df9daad3fdd09789f8e19c43b0aa3

commit_message:
Alarm: record history support

Ceilometer Alarm is able to record alarm change events.
This patch add this support in manifest.

Change-Id: Id8ece03dfd3491cd2886a345771df9622d702190
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Freeze iso8601 for older stable

As explained in Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
master bumped iso8601 version requirement to 0.1.8
but we can't do that on older stable branches, so cap the version instead.

Change-Id: I5677a294a1428774fc5c3b767bd4a7c8567d02ff

commit_message:
Pass Ironic API url to deploy ramdisk in PXE driver

Ironic's API url should be passed to deploy ramdisk for callback
via vendor passthru interface. API url gets from config option or
Keystone catalog.
Also node uuid used for deployment_id instead of id.

Change-Id: I8d190e107e73466fc96dd8896a8282bae22a020e

commit_message:
Add URLs from past TC/PPB/POC meetings

We need to go back through our past decisions and capture them in this
repo. Obviously that's going to take a lot of work, but a first step is
to be able to easily find the links to all previous meetings.

Change-Id: I73351b8db3c4d24283b5e011bf943c0a36b207f5

[{'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2013-11-07 03:29:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2013-11-07 04:31:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

I'm trying to understand, is this a motion to name these as core rather than integrated? 

Also is it Measurement or Metering? Who indicates this?"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-07 06:02:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, the motion is to include them in the list of projects under "Core OpenStack Project" as defined in the bylaws.

That's under the understanding that adding them to "Core OpenStack Project" does not mean they are required to be included in OpenStack products.

i.e. there are (at least) two different meanings of "core"


re: "Measurement" vs "Metering" - my understanding is that it's the former, but https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Ceilometer disagrees. I would have expected https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Ceilometer/Graduation or https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Governance/Proposed/Ceilometer to spell it out. Oh, and programs.yaml says Metering/Monitoring. Ok ... including ceilometer-core for clarification :)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-07 06:22:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Regarding metering vs. measurement, I think we never updated the wiki when we expanded to include monitoring. I like measurement better than the combination.'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-11-07 07:52:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think we used metering a lot, but measurement sounds like it would fit too. As I'm not a native English speaker, I've little clue on what would be the best term there."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-07 08:39:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Honestly, "Measurement" is a bit too abstract for my liking - not immediately obvious what it means. But that's just my $0.2c'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2013-11-07 09:09:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

One other bit of input, the latest user survey used "Metering" when asking about recent adoption.'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-10 23:00:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-11 00:39:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(2 inline comments)

OpenStack Measurements reflect the scope increase which happened during the second release.  Metering seems to only reflect the measurements intended for billing in my mind.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-11 08:26:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

As an aside, I find it strange that there are two meanings of 'core' floating around when the by-laws are quite clear as to what it means."}, {'account_id': 595, 'date': '2013-11-11 09:00:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

At the moment, people tend to confuse core for the following :
1/ What projects can call themselfves OpenStack
2/ What a distribution need to ship to call itself an OpenStack Distro
3/ What a cloud need to implement to call itself and OpenStack Cloud

I believe the bylaws only define 1, but the discussion at the board seemed to imply that 1 imply 2 and 3 which I think should be clearly dissociated.  We should be able to allow Ceilometer or Heat to be called OpenStack Measurements and Orchestration without implying that you need to ship it to call yourself and OpenStack Distro, nor implying that you need to implement them to call yourself an OpenStack Cloud.  These should be 3 separate decisions, not one.

Is that clearer?'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-11 10:04:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
resolution: official names for Ceilometer and Heat

During the Board of Directors meeting on Monday, it became clear that
there doesn't appear to be any controversy around allowing Ceilometer
and Heat use their official names.

The formal process in the bylaws is that the TC must recommend to the
board that they include the projects in the "Core OpenStack Project".

This commit proposes a resolution to this effect. The resolution also
makes it clear that we are not asking the board to require the use of
Heat and Ceilometer in products using the OpenStack trademark.

Change-Id: Ic751aa28b8f88e8c8d7f15b76bc1825725ac4c05

commit_message:
Stop using openstack.common.exception

The openstack.common.exception has been deprecated and removed from
oslo-incubator. Therefore, Ceilometer should follow the recommendation
and stop the usage of this file altogether.

Closes-Bug: #1208734
Change-Id: Ida4530d2f966f97b980db333f08a990250b7b68d

Nexenta iSCSI driver: extend volume stats of _update_volume_stats

Added location_info to stats provided by _update_volume_stats method
of Nexenta iSCSI volume driver.

Change-Id: Ib947180cb6d08d7639443a8998190ab911d1a4a4

Remove duplication of ISCSIDriver in ISERDriver

ISERDriver is almost copy of ISCSIDriver.

commit_message:
Split samples on deployments and tasks

The samples were reorganized, deployments and tasks are located in
different directories. Also, the deployment sample with DummyEngine
was added. The configuration samples was separated after implementation
of the blueprint independent-deploy.

Change-Id: Ic29b1b546cda38b14511e9601ce7b2aec48b82a6
Implements: blueprint logging

commit_message:
sync log from oslo

5fef5a8105 allow keeping of existing loggers with fileConfig
fb8075a19d Add amqp=WARN,qpid=WARN to default_log_levels
4654a5d247 Don't override default value for eventlet.wsgi.server logging
41ddd7a975 _get_log_file_path explictly return, when logfile/logdire unset
e12e6b45f8 Make openstack.common.log Python 3 compatible
572cfecb4d Make Messages unicode before hitting logging
3243cdfbe9 python3: handle module moves in log

DocImpact

Change-Id: I3f58066c6d18477ec7cfcfd610c71baae9b2e21f

commit_message:
Adopt 0.1.8 as iso8601 minimum version

In the images api, we depend on iso8601 to parse some dates and times.
Recently, since version 0.1.4, python-iso8601 added support for a few
more formats, and we finally got some other issues nailed down by 0.1.8.
If end user switch from 0.1.8 back to 0.1.4 in the deployment, the image
api will lose support for certain datetime formats like YYYY-MM-DD
(where the time part is assumed to be all zeros). This obviously creates
a compatibility concern.

We were resolved to make glance compatible with both iso 0.1.4 and
0.1.8, but it appears that to do so requires essentially reimplementing
a large swath of iso8601 0.1.8 in glance itself.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>
(cherry picked from commit c6cf12a22dd92873860c351f49e21c4b7296b155)

commit_message:
Fix django.conf.urls.defaults imports

These imports aren't available in Django 1.6. We need to use
django.conf.urls instead.

Partially-implements blueprint django-1point6

Change-Id: I692439a76de4fe5abff9ab9395bad5c10f1cdbba

commit_message:
cells/oslo.messaging: more idiomatic instantiation

Pdraig points out that:

  newobj = type(self)()

is more idiomatic than:

  newobj = self.__class__()

commit_message:
Retrieve volume image metadata using single query

The image metadata REST API contributions are making an individual db
call for each of the available volumes. When the number of volumes is
large the volume details call can take several minutes.

This patch changes the image metadata API contributions to take
advantage of the new db query to retrieve metadata in bulk.

Change-Id: I9a35438c1f38ea8a3d8f5b687ae58ba1f3f78121
Partial-Bug: #1197612

subject: Add call to retrieve image metadata for volumes in bulk

commit_message:
Add call to retrieve image metadata for volumes in bulk

When using the GET volume details REST API call, the image metadata API
contribution is making an individual db call for each of the available
volumes. When the number of volumes is large the details call can take
several minutes.

This patch adds a call to the volume.API to retrieve image metadata in
bulk, very similar to the one used to retrieve individual volume image
metadata.

Change-Id: Ic3aa721016704c72b7564cc5ceff71676806a24a
Partial-Bug: #1197612

commit_message:
Nexenta: Remove snapshot after volume-clone deletion.

Detect if volume was created via cloning and remove a snapshot from the
appliance if so. Return 'provider_location' to update the volume DB record
after creating a volume via cloning.

Closes-Bug: #1246079
Change-Id: I6c946d34871119600d7197614f5be22fa926e5dc

commit_message:
Markup models with confidentiality information

For our database continuous integration tests to start running in
public, we need to ensure that we don't leak confidential information
from test databases to gerrit. The plan here is to anonymize the
contents of the database to eliminate these data leakage issues.

We'd like to keep track of which columns to anonymize along side the
models, because it encourages others to keep the information in sync
when they change the schema. The information is packed into a variable
named __confidential__ once per class. It is hoped that this minimizes
the run time impact of this markup, whilst being less confusing than
doc comments.

Change-Id: I93842c6a18a57ccb24f6fe9c8858a1f7ac9bc60e

commit_message:
Add NOVA_BYPASS_URL as a recognized environment variable

nova supports --bypass-url as a command line argument but has no
corresponding environment variable.  This complicates using private api
endpoints with supernova.

Change-Id: Ief36008a0f59ee418345c974f25b5e88de0e0c92

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so we do it via
py3kcompat.

Sync the latest urlutils from oslo-incubator and use it.

Also remove py2.5 compat block since it is not tested
and not supported version of python for Openstack.

Change-Id: I89df2305997657421be0685b6dd219e602542d34
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>
'}]
commit_message:
python3: Use urlutils from oslo-incubator

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so we do it via
py3kcompat.

Sync the latest urlutils from oslo-incubator and use it.

Also remove py2.5 compat block since it is not tested
and not supported version of python for Openstack.

Change-Id: I89df2305997657421be0685b6dd219e602542d34
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

Add logging configuration for iso8601 module

iso8601 module outputs log messages but it is not useful for users,
so this commit assigns null log handler to iso8601 module.
This change suppresses iso8601 log messages during unit tests.

Also moves openstack_dashboard related logging config for unit test
from horizon to openstack_dashboard.

Change-Id: I01cf12688118e2137382b8dc7a050b3587749354
Closes-Bug: #1250554

commit_message:
RequestContext initialization failed in cinder.

RequestContext initialization failed in cinder because of the following
error:
"TypeError: 'in <string>' requires string as left operand, not NoneType"

It must traverses in tuple not in string when find the "compute"
service_catalog.

Change-Id: I46f4bbd0ffb9d1db8bdcb0254ca95551fea08baf
Closes-Bug: #1248434

[{'created': '2013-11-05 21:00:48.000000000', 'message': "Remove some WebOb leftovers.

The deleted comments were talking about a swob EmptyResponse object,
which doesn't exist; it seems this was left over from the big WebOb
removal. Also, swob doesn't exhibit that behavior, so there's no point
in having this extra code path around.

Further, it seems like the hack was only needed with WebOb < 1.0.8. I
went back to Swift 1.4.8 (Essex) and compared it to master, and this
is the result:

DLO manifest HEAD
=================

Essex (ffadbc3)
---------------
Small #segments --> Content-Length: 12345
Large #segments --> Content-Length: 0
Large #segments sans shenanigans --> Content-Length: 0

master (f63b58f)
----------------
Small #segments --> Content-Length: 12345
Large #segments --> Content-Length: 0
Large #segments sans shenanigans --> Content-Length: 0

So, whatever WebOb wackiness this was intended to hack around, it
doesn't seem to have been here for a long, long time.

Change-Id: I7b717b1b36de1139cc5b76c166d1715dbc34b332
"}]
commit_message:
Remove some WebOb leftovers.

The deleted comments were talking about a swob EmptyResponse object,
which doesn't exist; it seems this was left over from the big WebOb
removal. Also, swob doesn't exhibit that behavior, so there's no point
in having this extra code path around.

Further, it seems like the hack was only needed with WebOb < 1.0.8. I
went back to Swift 1.4.8 (Essex) and compared it to master, and this
is the result:

DLO manifest HEAD
=================

Essex (ffadbc3)
---------------
Small #segments --> Content-Length: 12345
Large #segments --> Content-Length: 0
Large #segments sans shenanigans --> Content-Length: 0

master (f63b58f)
----------------
Small #segments --> Content-Length: 12345
Large #segments --> Content-Length: 0
Large #segments sans shenanigans --> Content-Length: 0

So, whatever WebOb wackiness this was intended to hack around, it
doesn't seem to have been here for a long, long time.

Change-Id: I7b717b1b36de1139cc5b76c166d1715dbc34b332

commit_message:
Removed instructions to copy .conf files

Bug 1247323 states a requirement to remove the
instructions to copy .conf files between the controller and compute
nodes. Bug 1245968 mentions this as a possible cause of the issue.
This patch progresses both bugs, but resolves neither. Also fixes for
some minor layout and wording issues.

Change-Id: Ia92fbaf9152df561aa38dac4c91e9f38bd425964
backport: havana
Partial-Bug: #1247323
Partial-Bug: #1245968
(cherry picked from commit 7d39198c1f5dd05af6d4b368c78f4fee3532a99d)

commit_message:
Add step for "Compute and Network Node - L2 Agent" install  instructions

Adds step, formats it for rhel, centos, fedora

Creates a symbolic link from /etc/neutron/plugin.ini to /etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini or neutron-server will not run on Centos

Change-Id: I5f5e31f315237d6eeb6a51d28e3dc799081a43a7
author: nermina miller
backport: havana

(cherry picked from commit 63a0babcf38c3c0d824a4e54c4c89f5c1658c48a)

Looking at a `mysqldump` of my database I pulled from a backup a week ago before I updated my system to Ubuntu 13.10 it appears it ended up with two identical constraints with different names:

--
-- Table structure for table `instance_info_caches`
--

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `instance_info_caches`;
/*!40101 SET @saved_cs_client     = @@character_set_client */;
/*!40101 SET character_set_client = utf8 */;
CREATE TABLE `instance_info_caches` (
  `created_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `updated_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `deleted_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `id` int(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
  `network_info` mediumtext,
  `instance_uuid` varchar(36) NOT NULL,
  `deleted` int(11) DEFAULT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`),
  UNIQUE KEY `instance_uuid` (`instance_uuid`),
  CONSTRAINT `instance_info_caches_ibfk_1` FOREIGN KEY (`instance_uuid`) REFERENCES `instances` (`uuid`),
  CONSTRAINT `instance_info_caches_instance_uuid_fkey` FOREIGN KEY (`instance_uuid`) REFERENCES `instances` (`uuid`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=202 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8;
/*!40101 SET character_set_client = @saved_cs_client */;


So the patch removes one, but not both, of the constraints."}, {'account_id': 6849, 'date': '2013-10-29 08:23:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'll be working further on this today.

Josh"}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2013-10-30 03:44:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Fix migration 185 to work with old fkey names

Migration 133_folsom.py accidentally changed the name of the FK
constraint on instance_info_caches from instance_info_caches_ibfk_1
to instance_info_caches_instance_uuid_fkey and on virtual_interfaces
from virtual_interfaces_ibfk_1 to
virtual_interfaces_instance_uuid_fkey meaning databases who have
upgraded from before folsom have the old fkey.

This patch adds a check for those with the old fkey name to make sure
it is dropped before changing unique constraints (as is required by
MySQL). It also fixes the fkey name to be as defined in 133 if it
wasn't before (which will persist on downgrade being consistent with
those who have come in after folsom).

Closes-Bug: #1245502

Change-Id: Ib0dcd04fcb9ed776c76d40561181abad2e14f76f

commit_message:
Replace assertEquals with assertEqual - tests/etc

The method assertEquals has been deprecated since python 2.7.
http://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#deprecated-aliases

Also in Python 3, a deprecated warning is raised when using assertEquals
therefore we should use assertEqual instead.

This is part of blueprint assertequal

Change-Id: I5ecb36332b9353b7010a4f977813ff0295738014

In general looks great.

One thought that occurred when reviewing this patch is that we have a number of places where we are using

  log.debug(msg % params)

where we probably should be using

  log.debug(msg, params)

for better performance. But I think that is a separate concern so I don't think its a problem with this patch.

The only reason why I'm a +1 and not a +2 is that this patch does make minor changes to previous migrations. The changes seem correct (and preserve functional equivalence) but I'm curious if they're really necessary.

See http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-October/017997.html for more details."}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2013-11-10 04:50:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

FWIW, I don't think this patch needs to address changing from
  msg = _(...) % params
  log.info(msg)
to
  msg = _(...)
  log.info(msg, params)
although I do prefer the second approach when the formatted message is not going to be reused.


Two questions that have come up from further review, however. First, is there any hacking check we can turn on to ensure we don't accidentally start using locals() again? Second, I noticed some places where the message changes from something like
  msg = _("Some message and %(blah)s")
to
  msg = _("Some message and %s")

While the change matches our style guidelines, I'm curious if we are creating a bunch of translation work that we don't need to? Would it save work for downstream translators if we kept the named substitution in these cases?

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-11-11 21:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thank you,'}, {'account_id': 2537, 'date': '2013-11-11 21:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (11 inline comments)

Thanks for pointing out that Mark, I noted down the places where it formatting could be avoided at the string level and passed down to the logger.

Also, some interesting points can be seen here http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5082452/python-string-formatting-vs-format. Firstly, the style 

"str %s" % var can cause type errors on tuples. And down near the bottom (3rd last comment as of 2013-11-11) they ask to use advanced string (beneficial while switching to python 3 as well)

As Mark says, these changes are not necessary. (So don't have a -1) However, if we include certain changes to this patch we might as well include as per some of the observations above.'}, {'account_id': 7996, 'date': '2013-11-11 21:46:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Remove use of locals() when creating messages

Per the hacking guidelines locals() should not be used when creating
messages, but additionally this is preparation for upcoming message
internationalization work.

Change-Id: I9ce616b94faf2d7df895c6bffb94baac8c82c7ce

[{'created': '2013-11-11 19:09:55.000000000', 'message': 'Fix cmd usage msg for ironic port-create

The arguments --address and --node_id are mandatory arguments for
ironic port-create, but are listed as optional arguments in usage message.
This change fixes them.

commit_message:
Fix cmd usage msg for ironic port-create

The arguments --address and --node_id are mandatory arguments for
ironic port-create, but are listed as optional arguments in usage message.
This change fixes them.

Change-Id: I3a32577140021ce77706c73f8cc21842ea5f0473
Closes-Bug: #1244637

commit_message:
Don't zero out thin provisioned LV's on delete

Thin provisioned LV's don't need secure delete to protect
from data leakage.  Also, zeroing these out kinda defeats
the purpose of using thing provisioning.

This patch add a check for the lvm type and if it's thin simply
returns from the lvm.clear_volume() method.

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_volume.py
	cinder/volume/drivers/lvm.py

Change-Id: Ie6764209018152565295291efc6fbba553698ae6
Closes-Bug: #1240299
(cherry picked from commit de4392314f9b0def8fab65679ec5668aec98fbee)

commit_message:
Avoid using 'which' executable for finding git

Just use 'git --version' to check if the git executable is present

Change-Id: Ib5c11060fa7d9b7d9741dd88fc3430237f0bc1a0
Closes-Bug: #1248447

commit_message:
Add ability to override the RandomString value

Give the RandomString a parameter that allows an arbitrary value to be
resolved via the value attribute. This gives the RandomString resource
the ability to be used as a default for a string parameter.

Change-Id: I0b86ea8550e38181f1b7024a430fd5136bdc8e2d

commit_message:
Remove the warning for Scheduling Network

when a new port is created, the schedule_network in agentschedulers_db is called.
Since this network may already be hosted, it will directly return None in dhcp_agent_scheduler,
which cause the agentschedulers_db.schedule_network log a warning message.

This is really annoying and making users confused.
And, real warnings are already addressed in the real scheduler function.
which is neutron.scheduler.dhcp_agent_scheduler.ChanceScheduler.schedule by default.

Change-Id: I11bdbe47c2cc0fc45fb143970fb6762678bc27e5
Closes-Bug: #1192786

@Zhongyue, why deprecate this? I can see both nova and cinder need this util, it is better that we still keep it.

====================================
nova uses this all over the place to check if a string is a uuid; can we move that function into nova and deprecate/delete this module?
===================================='}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-11-12 15:44:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

The plan is to deprecate generate_uuid() because it is trivial. The matching function is buggy, but after it is fixed will probably stay.

From what I understand, generate_uuid() was created to ensure that everyone remembered to use the string representation of the UUID object returned from uuid4(). This new function seems to indicate that the string representation is not what we want in all cases. Given that, I'm even more inclined to just remove generate_uuid() and require users of the uuid module to understand how it works."}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-11-13 01:46:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Adandon for now'}]

commit_message:
Add a new function to generate pure uuid in oslo

Now in oslo, it only has a function to generate uuid in string
format but no pure uuid format. In some functions, it does need
this format, such as getting hex value for uuid: uuid.uuid4().hex

The fix was add a new function named as get_pure_uuid() to generate
pure uuid without any format change.

Change-Id: Ie139b748e9297ef4338daa5bca8fd2c7fc4406fc

[{'created': '2013-11-12 02:21:44.000000000', 'message': 'Add TOCI_UNDERCLOUD_EXTRA_ELEMENTS

Add a new option which can be used to configure extra elements used
for undercloudy (seed vm and undercloud) images. This can be
useful if you are using non-standard power drivers and need extra
things injected into your undercloud images. Or perhaps you

Add TOCI_UNDERCLOUD_EXTRA_ELEMENTS

for the undercloud image. Useful for ad-hoc testing of elements for
undercloud images.

commit_message:
Ignore duplicate service_providers and log warning

Changes behavior of provider_configuration.py to detect if
duplicate service_providers were specified. If a duplicate
is detected a warning message is logged and duplicate
provider is ignored.

Closes-Bug 1250664

Change-Id: I3f8fe333be076aa91befec8a30f12d072bc01884

commit_message:
Python code refactorings.

This commit refactors the python code in diskimage_builder slightly.  This is
in preparation for a larger review that adds more functionality to the python
code, namely the ability to apply elements to the current system as opposed to
a chroot.  Further, the refactorings can stand on their own for better clarity.
They include:
 - renaming elements.py to element_dependencies.py.  Adds clarity about the
   purpose of this module.
 - updating other code for this rename.
 - move tests into a tests submodule.

Change-Id: I5519cc52398e442b24e33802bae42070d64b0c1d

commit_message:
Report zero capacity if GPFS is unmounted

_get_available_capacity() calls df command to gather the capacity of GPFS
filesystem. If GPFS is unmounted, df command will return the capacity of
root file system. This change will let get_volume_stats() to report zero
capacity, so that Cinder can schedule the volume request to another volume
service After GPFS is mounted again, the correct capacity will be reported.

Change-Id: I4c229d78e7d659604a23a50e6ab46060642b4088
Closes-Bug: #1246779

commit_message:
Do not remove volume silently if GPFS is unmounted

When GPFS is not mounted, delete_volume() will complete successfully, so that
volume record is removed by cinder but volume file still resides on GPFS. This
change will prevent cinder to remove volume when GPFS is not mounted.

Change-Id: Ic3bf265e553f22c8b6a6e3568da04af88fab3322
Closes-Bug: #1249411

[{'created': '2013-11-12 23:47:30.000000000', 'message': "Closes-Bug: 1247296

Always upload a snapshot as a preallocated disk

Currently, a snapshot operation always produces a preallocated disk type. When the snapshot is
uploaded to glance, the source image metadata is uploaded with the new snapshot and then some of
the metadata properties are updated. The update doesn't include the disk_type property, this can be
problematic. If the original image has a sparse disk type and a snapshot is taken, then the snapshot
which is a preallocated disk type is uploaded to glance with the disk_type  property set to sparse,
which creates a type mismatch and causes errors when a vm is spawned from that snapshot. This patch
addresses the issue by correcting the image metadata used when uploading a snapshot to glance.

Also, the image_upload function in vmwareapi/fake.py has been modified to address the change. Any
function call to image_upload (from the unit tests) will assert that the metadata for the image to be
uploaded must have the disk_type value to be preallocated.

Change-Id: I10d1548e54faeb337e710fb6775f4a7bbb317bcd
"}]
commit_message:
Closes-Bug: 1247296

Always upload a snapshot as a preallocated disk

Currently, a snapshot operation always produces a preallocated disk type. When the snapshot is
uploaded to glance, the source image metadata is uploaded with the new snapshot and then some of
the metadata properties are updated. The update doesn't include the disk_type property, this can be
problematic. If the original image has a sparse disk type and a snapshot is taken, then the snapshot
which is a preallocated disk type is uploaded to glance with the disk_type  property set to sparse,
which creates a type mismatch and causes errors when a vm is spawned from that snapshot. This patch
addresses the issue by correcting the image metadata used when uploading a snapshot to glance.

Also, the image_upload function in vmwareapi/fake.py has been modified to address the change. Any
function call to image_upload (from the unit tests) will assert that the metadata for the image to be
uploaded must have the disk_type value to be preallocated.

Change-Id: I10d1548e54faeb337e710fb6775f4a7bbb317bcd

commit_message:
Add a status message to the README

The client status was not known to me and this provides a way
for users to get started without getting frustrated with actually
trying to use the client.

Thanks to malini on IRC for the examples.

This should be removed as soon as the client is functional.

commit_message:
Removes unused paste appserver instances from tests

Paste application servers were being created and never actually used.
The only thing that was used was the side effect of setting the public
and admin ports. This reduces the overall process footprint.

Change-Id: I8d5753cbc0970678baed7a873280bac06faa9a53
Partial-Bug: #1247443

Move various plugin configuration info from the old networking install chapter to Cloud Admin Guide

Move Big Switch, Nicira, OSV, PLUMgrid, Ryu, and neutron agent config info to ch_neworking
Add info about deleting nova-network before initializing networking install
Add crossreferences to Config Ref and Install Guide

commit_message:
Add step for "Compute and Network Node - L2 Agent" install  instructions

Adds step, formats it for rhel, centos, fedora

Creates a symbolic link from /etc/neutron/plugin.ini to /etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini or neutron-server will not run on Centos

Change-Id: I5f5e31f315237d6eeb6a51d28e3dc799081a43a7
author: nermina miller
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: 1240697

commit_message:
Add missing CLI Neutron tests

This adds:
* lb-healthmonitor-list
* lb-member-list
* lb-pool-list
* lb-vip-list

commit_message:
Add log_handler to implement the publish_errors config option

Synced from Olso.
Commit Id is Ibf28ba17f81b5ddeda653f6a3501ecac18ffcd42

This handler sends all error logs as rpc notifications.
Note: when using publish_errors you also need to set the
notification_driver option too.

Change-Id: Ic97b9c8b84d51c84a53ace5b86cc2e72c744f136
Closes-bug: #1240349

commit_message:
Fix NameError exception

The test_allocate_floating_ip can fail with "NameError:
name 'floating_ip_id_allocated' is not defined" if the
client.create_floating_ip call or response return fail.

Change-Id: I2db82ecf560c7d868ca9ab765a4fd751946b45f0

This will make log_handler automatically synced with log. This is
necessary because log adds a config option 'publish_error' that
requires log_handler.

Related-Bug: #1240349
"}]
commit_message:
Makes log_hander a real dependency of log

This will make log_handler automatically synced with log. This is

commit_message:
Moving mgmt host tests.

* Move mgmt tests to trove
* Deleting rackspace specific tests
* fixing internal references to test_config
* refactored out global variables to use trove.test.config
* refactored int_tests.py to allow extending or removing tests
* refactored colorizer to cut down on logic in int_tests.py

Implements: Blueprint host-mgmt-tests

Change-Id: Iddb44083d2eeb27b066880609f13d7ded4af8372

[{'created': '2013-11-12 02:47:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes NTP advices

Previously, the install-guide told about using the "ntpdate"
client in a cron job to update the time, which is a bad
advise. Also, it didn't tell how to install ntpdate either.
Using the ntp daemon is much better. This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: I6f624cf89d558bffcaee724e13274466a8fd3e2b
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 265486355daa6c58c3ab9e62c26754671aae4934)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes NTP advices

Previously, the install-guide told about using the "ntpdate"
client in a cron job to update the time, which is a bad
advise. Also, it didn't tell how to install ntpdate either.
Using the ntp daemon is much better. This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: I6f624cf89d558bffcaee724e13274466a8fd3e2b
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 265486355daa6c58c3ab9e62c26754671aae4934)

commit_message:
curl to wget in verify image service installation

Changing "curl" to "wget" in "Verifying the Image Service installation"
 page. This is because Ubuntu doesn't include curl in the default
base/minimal installation.

Change-Id: I16364d05085a2a9c3713e94f71a3250215361540
Closes-Bug: #1248605
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit de0eb7db9081743f7e46d853056f66b251c047b0)
