commit_message:
Document quantum-ovs-cleanup

Adds some documentation about the need for quantum-ovs-cleanup
to ensure that DHCP agent and L3 agent perform properly on reboot.

Also changes: plugin -> plug-in

Change-Id: I063c5e911d0f26c5704b24713b13d8909c1d319f
Partial-Bug: 1156861

commit_message:
Add WSGI environment to context

The environment dictionary contains an unspecified set of variables
that contain information about the authentication and authorization
processes.  Not all of the values are known ahead of time.  The
two values for Kerberos (REMOTE_USER, AUTH_TYPE) are a subset.

Instead of making the WSGI layer know about a growing superset of
authentication attributes, the context contains a link to the wsgi
environment.  The environment is removed from the request dictionary
to prevent circular references and potential GC issues.

Fixed tests  to set environment in the context.  While this
changed many tests, the alternative was to make the check
for the environment optional in the controllers.  This is not a
realistic way to test.  If context['environment'] it missing, a test
will trigger a key_error.

Closes-Bug: #1241812

Change-Id: I234677547204e9ddc0ab33db3e6aa8b7d959a01a

commit_message:
Preparing for 2.2.1 release

This patch bumps the Modulefile release number. The 2.2.0
release of stable/grizzly depended on the wrong concat module.
The 2.2.1 release will correct the packaged module.

Change-Id: I636cda1e6c05cb95953de159d22d07e2135d349d

commit_message:
Rename to create_test_server in API tests

There are two methods of the name create_server().
The one is a client which just sends a request for creating a server
instance.
The other is BaseComputeTest class' which sends the same request,
registers the created server to the list for deleting it after test,
and waits for the server status change.

They would be confusing due to the same name, and there is unnecessary
addCleanup() calls for deleting a server.

This patch renames the one of BaseComputeTest to create_test_server for
making the difference clear, and removes unnecessary addCleanup() call.

Change-Id: If09fc09f77d27a48dc19dd2dbc47ea460b0c7920

commit_message:
Fix assignment to not use identity

The SQL and LDAP assignment backends are using the identity API
when there should be no calls from assignment backend to identity
API.

commit_message:
Gracefully handle request for binary data as plain

This will return a 406 instead of a 500 in the event that a user
requests binary data but provides text/plain as the content type
that they accept.

Change-Id: I003c8306138db7d8d53d30c2e83f29a51aa3759d
Closes-Bug: #1220957

commit_message:
assertTrue to assertIn

* replacing the assertTrue where simply replaceable with assertIn
* The assertTrue(len(foo)>1) style extended with str(foo) details,
  where expected len is greater than 1.

Change-Id: I7515e879e3e24ce041a4fcae63d9d4a5f257f37d

commit_message:
Use a @cached_property decorator

Instead of using an ugly code that uses __dict__ or hasattr,
use a @cached_property decorator that encapsulates the
property caching logic in a single place and makes it easier
to later replace with better caching techniques.

Re-use the cached_property from django.

Change-Id: I9e3e26cd4a8c7055854e851bc5f062a29981971e

When the session expires and horizon does an Ajax call (for example,
to get a modal window), an exception is raised instead of redirecting
to the login screen, because the exception handler in the horizon
middleware doesn't add the "horizon" attribute to the request. This is
a very simple fix to avoid throwing the exception.

Change-Id: I663999dd616b1a4fa3292615eecf3cc44c3e808a
Closes-bug: #1224458
'}]
commit_message:
Fix AttributeError on Ajax calls with expired session

When the session expires and horizon does an Ajax call (for example,
to get a modal window), an exception is raised instead of redirecting
to the login screen, because the exception handler in the horizon
middleware doesn't add the "horizon" attribute to the request. This is
a very simple fix to avoid throwing the exception.

Change-Id: I663999dd616b1a4fa3292615eecf3cc44c3e808a
Closes-bug: #1224458

commit_message:
Remove Celery and Kombu version pinning

The pinned version of Kombu was incompatible with the latest un-pinned
version of Celery. Removing this pinning fixed the issue.

Change-Id: I868c86ac67350e6429ce806af3385623c8931548

'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-10-25 15:27:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

So the fix now looks good - we are missing tests stil. 

This is a nice fix since it moves the headroom calculations into the quota module (kind of) where they indeed belong. We do need to make sure there are no logical errors in our code, since if those sneak in - architectural errors that we fixed don't matter as much.

The best place to add tests for the bugfix in this case is nova.tests.test_quota module. If you take a look at the code there there is the QuotaIntegrationTestCase class and all it does is tests that the compute_api methods that can raise a QuotaError do so. We need to make sure it does not in this particular case - but you can get the idea from other tests there.

You also change the db.sqlalchemy.api.quota_reserve. That method is horrible so much so that it actually has it's own testcase outside of normal place in nova.tests.test_quota.QuotaReserveSqlAlchemyTestCase so that would be a good place to add a few test cases for the logic itself. Now afaict - there are no tests that actually check the kwargs of the raised OverQuota. It would be good to add such a test and then make sure our new headroom logic is sound.

Finally you mess with the limit_check method of the DbQuotaDriver and it's tests seem to be localized to nova.tests.DbQuotaDriverTestCase so just add a test there.

#protip grepping for all the places where something is used and then checking the files that belong to tests module is a good way to figure out how something is tested in nova :)"}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-11-02 06:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Abandoned

commit_message:
Moved quota headroom calculations into quota_reserve

Moved headroom calculations into quota_reserve and modified headroom
calculations to take into account -ve quota limits (unlimited) on
cores and ram.

Updated test cases to generate OverQuota exceptions with new headroom
parameter.

Added new tests for 'unlimited' quotas to test_quota.py in
 QuotaIntegrationTestCase and DbQuotaDriverTestCase classes.

Add Exception kwargs checking for OverQuota and QuotaError exceptions.

Change-Id: I855b0cad495182c5c4ee42b2acf5eedd198557b5
Closes-Bug: #1224453 min_count ignored for instance create

commit_message:
Install Guide: Use controller also for Ubuntu for sql_connection

We use for other distributions controller instead of localhost in
the connection string, use controller as well for Ubuntu

Change-Id: Ifd11c08300f10ed0dd50cd060afe03b3e6f18493
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1248603
(cherry picked from commit 56144af276484e11b0b69a1e0e6344e5006fb8cc)

[{'created': '2013-11-11 13:14:01.000000000', 'message': "Rename variables called 'fixtures'

'fixtures' is the name of a library used by OpenStack. Some variables
in the code were using the same name and potentially could cause cause
some confusion when reading the code.

commit_message:
Rename variables called 'fixtures'

'fixtures' is the name of a library used by OpenStack. Some variables
in the code were using the same name and potentially could cause cause
some confusion when reading the code.

Change-Id: I25b4c969b9fcdc56d4eeb46ed8e8aa51b73682a7

commit_message:
Supporting both Python 2 and Python 3 with six

As we know python3 will not support built-in basestring, so we
should use 'six' to support both python2 and python3.

Change-Id: I9bad381f175602322cb750d6c1b62beeee222cb2
Partial-Bug: #1249886

commit_message:
Fix error handling in ssh driver

_get_power_status() of ironic.drivers.modules.ssh driver
should raise an exception NodeNotFound instead of returning
states.ERROR, when the node is actually not found.

Closes-Bug: #1201964
Change-Id: I1193b0efef93dd7bf5e99cfa009da47882d53057

commit_message:
Check invalid uuid for get-by-instance db api

The db api get_node_by_instance did not check if the given
instance uuid is a valid uuid or not. This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: Ic22e0bf5db34fdd3d8ef974f40ea3a736ee95525

commit_message:
Remove "image_cache_invalid_entry_grace_period" option

 "image_cache_invalid_entry_grace_period" option is unused
in *.py, but the option is used in glance-cache.conf.

 I removed "image_cache_invalid_entry_grace_period" option
from glance-cache.conf.

Change-Id: Id235945f9cc89219118e4a3ec077f0e887a3b3ef
Closes-Bug: #1249949

commit_message:
Ceilometer installation fixes

- MongoDB must be configured to accept connections on the public
  interface of the controller on (Open)SUSE and Debian/Ubuntu
- Fix wrong section name for the metering_key setting

Change-Id: I98a0278c08d40faa6f5f0a8c44f28bd17b274b32
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 65f4b44b366bc469df053ce5bc1fa91c5d2a208f)

commit_message:
Remove unused method setup_logging

Method setup_logging in glance/common/config.py wasn't used anywhere.
Similar function is in oslo, and some modules in Glance are using
function log.setup from oslo, like glance/cmd/manage.py#L123

Closes-Bug: #1248214

Change-Id: Icda26943f02df5e495179868aa8b1f4c4e151803

commit_message:
Removed instructions to copy .conf files

Bug 1247323 states a requirement to remove the
instructions to copy .conf files between the controller and compute
nodes. Bug 1245968 mentions this as a possible cause of the issue.
This patch progresses both bugs, but resolves neither. Also fixes for
some minor layout and wording issues.

Change-Id: Ia92fbaf9152df561aa38dac4c91e9f38bd425964
backport: havana
Partial-Bug: #1247323
Partial-Bug: #1245968

commit_message:
Adjust most str usage to the proper bytes/text

Using six's text_type, binary_type, and string_types, this change makes
more code work on Python 3 where the distinction between byte strings
and Unicode strings is stronger.

Change-Id: Iaa80eae5032ddf9c67c5e095dddada5ea4b1dea9

commit_message:
Install Guide: Make titles consistent

We have mixed styles in the guide with regards to capitalization
and do not use gerunds (_ING_ verbs). This fixes the remaining
pieces.

Change-Id: I20a45b77de267a946b8f5b24c4a54fb9461274d0
backport: havana

commit_message:
Remove bad parameter for cfg.get

when loading from cfg file, cfg.get takes just 2 parameters not
three.

Added some basic tests and test for the specific change as well

commit_message:
Using a number in str_replace causes an exception

When passing in a number as a parameter value to the string replace
function, an exception is raised. Cast the value as a string before
using it in the string replace function.

Change-Id: I38bdc8d97c7d1f9b62f52b0a783bf4d3fde3611a
Closes-Bug: #1250251

Move exception registration to a separate file

Add exception handling in service_catalog view
Remove exception part from setup scripts ans settings.py

Switch base unit test class to oslo mox fixture

tempest.tests.base and instead uses the MoxStubout fixture from oslo.

commit_message:
Skip all nova v3 tests temporarily

For making one nova v3 parameter consistent, some patch is review
in progress now (I452672e064d0dc4a1d5700bb96c01de8087f33d8).
The parameter is used at many places, and we need to skip nova v3
tests temporarily to merge the patch.
After merging the patch, we will enable the tests again with changing
the parameter in Tempest.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests
Change-Id: I51be1cb5be312d2b099f74c70a49a9e58765d3d8

commit_message:
Sync iso8601 requirement and fixes test case failures

1. Sync requirements from global Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
2. iso8601>=0.1.7 "parse_date()" could successfully handle date string
which only have date part like YYYY-MM-DD, it caused two Glance test
cases failure.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: I2625eb3888111829a9da4d093b34193b8795f264
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8160ae293383ec600c05fd2e4b38164bca7704c4)
Conflicts:
	glance/tests/unit/v1/test_api.py
	glance/tests/unit/v1/test_registry_api.py
	tools/pip-requires

commit_message:
Add time unit constants in units module

Almost every OpenStack project is using hardcode to calculate duration
like 'delta.days * 24 * 3600', even 2592000, We'd better use time unit
constants to clean up code.

Change-Id: Ia6623fd38c33c36df8801fca6e224e9f31a4d5bf

commit_message:
Add additional documentation for stress tests

In order to encourage people to add more and more stress tests we
need more documentation about it. This documents the stresstest
decorator and gives a global overview.

Change-Id: I65294fb278faba7a0d324782bf50e2fdedc5c1de

Add more stuff to SAIO doc's proxy pipeline.

If you're setting one of these up, you're probably going to use it for
development, in which case you want everything but the kitchen sink
turned on so you can just start hacking away.

commit_message:
Remove database section from plugin.ini

Change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34515 moved the database
config items to neutron.conf but left some commented out
[database] items. Remove them as well.

Closes-Bug: #1247589

commit_message:
Rename exception NoUniqueImageFound

It is now called PhysicalResourceNameAmbiguity and can
be used where looking up a physical resource by name results
in more than one resource being returned.

Change-Id: Ib6d03a4eac6dc674378b2f2619383d8d0f3dd25e

commit_message:
Replacing iptables FORWARD filter

The seed VM is acting as a gateway so the REJECT rule needs to be removed
to allow overcloud nodes access to the outside world. Since we are now
blanket accepting packets to be forwarded, the old filters that allowed
forwarding into cloud nodes can now be removed.

Change-Id: I6e93d4a2fa9514e27ecdd5c460e7ba99e736d07f

commit_message:
Adds "list hosts" test case - Cinder

This submission adds a new test script in volume admin api catogery,
so as to verify list hosts functionality in cinder API. Also added
required support functions in the corresponding files of both JSON/XML
interfaces.

Implements blueprint: cinder-grizzly1-blueprints-implementation

Change-Id: Ibe4e226e0cf26ac80594aa9717f7d4715be54734

- check-grenade-devstack-vm http://logs.openstack.org/68/52768/1/check/check-grenade-devstack-vm/6e483a9 : SUCCESS in 26m 22s
'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-10-20 00:55:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Though fuzz testing would be a big win, unfortunately I don't think we can get away nearly this easily. Here are some issues that come to mind:

1. The negative tests, fuzzed or not, really should go against the REST api as they do now.

2. We really want to check for bad types and fencepost errors, not random values, which require knowing the actual types/ranges of the arguments. If we had json schema for each api that would be ideal or even xml schema. I don't know how many of our apis actually have that but my memory is that it is not too many.

3. The negative tests need to know what code is being returned which needs the same kind of schema info.

4. A proper blasting using real servers like tempest does would take a long time. Perhaps this sort of thing would be better as part of the unit test framework?

This is all hard. I suppose there could be value in doing this the easy way even if it is far from what we would really want but I'm not sure how much."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-10-20 03:19:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

On further thought, these kinds of tests really have to be in tempest to test regressions about negative behavior.'}, {'account_id': 6743, 'date': '2013-10-20 08:29:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

Please check my comments'}, {'account_id': 5586, 'date': '2013-10-20 15:21:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 7872, 'date': '2013-10-21 06:22:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@David:
Thanks for your thoughts about it. I really wanted to start with something easy just to start with a discussion. Here my thoughts about your objections:

1-3.) To remove the negative tests we need to check the response and verify it. For fuzzy testing in general this isn't really needed. So I could improve it in that way. I am thinking on a little library that generates "negative" test cases out of the box.

2.) So far I see the negative tests are using client api calls which lead to REST api calls. I agree that interface schemas as input would be great and flexible. But not that easy :) Using the client functions has the advantage that it's already a representation of a schema in python code.'}, {'account_id': 1119, 'date': '2013-10-28 13:01:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Nice work, Marc!

Adding to the topic of fuzzying the APIs, I wanted to point to some work Thomas Biege (SUSE) did a while ago, that is partly documented here: http://thetoms-random-thoughts.blogspot.de/2011/01/tool-owasp-test-suite.html and https://github.com/SUSE-Cloud/automation/blob/master/scripts/qa_crowbarsetup.sh#L1046-1075 -- and of course in code, here: https://gitorious.org/~thomasbiege, git@gitorious.org:test-suite/test-suite.git (fuzz_xmlrpc.pl) (unfortunately gitorious.org is down at the time of commenting here).

I would probably be good, to take the security / OWASP fuzzing into consideration for this as well. Unfortunately, the implementation of Thomas is in perl, IIRC.'}, {'account_id': 7872, 'date': '2013-11-12 05:29:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Will be covered in https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tempest/+spec/negative-tests'}]

commit_message:
Fuzzy test tool for client functions

In order to reduce the number of negative test it's helpful to have
a tool that generates random values for a certain client function.
This tool discovers the parameters of a given client manager function
and generates random values with different data types.

The goal of this tool is to break the API by passing invalid data
through.

TODOS:

  - Add parameter/check to validate the health of the server at the
    end.

Change-Id: Iaf07447df6d57ae95f08add3dc0a85d9f63312e5

commit_message:
xenapi: Move settings to their own config section

This commit changes xenapi_* config options to their own section
with the xenapi_ prefix removed where appropriate.  The change
is done in a backwards compatible fashion such that previous
nova.conf files still work.

As part of this update the sample file and text strings are
also updated to reflect new config options.  Test cases have
been adjusted to handle the config hierarchy.

2642897d6f5b8a211424519d99feddc89c3bf180 was followed to
implement this change.

Change-Id: I2e9f720ddce284fc112d6a5651fd277e6e31a17a
Closes-Bug: 1207253
DocImpact

commit_message:
Fix python 3.x related Hacking warnings

Convert print operator usages to print functions.
Fix one instance of outdated "except x,y:" syntactical construct.
Remove usages of local() in string formatting alongway.

Change-Id: Id0673a9183a6ea6bd9bf3f5c6d8e7c5f114ebf01

commit_message:
Make the vmware pause/unpause unit tests actually test something

The pause/unpause tests for vmware were just passing so this patch
actually makes them test the pause/unpause methods for the
VMwareESXDriver and VMwareVCDriver classes.

Closes-Bug: #1237679

Change-Id: Idf7c6e6f9542b9ab4dd2ab710597f1a198889dfa

commit_message:
Implement update for neutron port resources

This change allows any updatable properties to be updated
on an existing port without replacement. Documentation
is limited on what properties are updatable, so discovery
was manual. Unlike other neutron resources, port name is not
updateable without replacement.

Change-Id: I7845702e14baab595363d57bcf6128e45ffdd789
Closes-Bug: #1241553

commit_message:
Implement update for neutron router resources

This change allows any updatable properties to be updated
on an existing router without replacement. Documentation
is limited on what properties are updatable, so discovery
was manual.

Partial-Bug: #1241553
Change-Id: Ia3b1885cee2f3440bb73724291d46d5af19962eb

commit_message:
curl to wget in verify image service installation

Changing "curl" to "wget" in "Verifying the Image Service installation"
 page. This is because Ubuntu doesn't include curl in the default
base/minimal installation.

Change-Id: I16364d05085a2a9c3713e94f71a3250215361540
Closes-Bug: #1248605
backport: havana

commit_message:
use different bind addresses for admin and public

Keystone supports configuration of an admin_port and a public_port.
Applications may well want the admin port to be open on a different private network.
This patch change single bind_host to public_bind_host and admin_bind_host in the configuration.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic91aade987724c8f7c9276ca94e27681ae590662
Closes-Bug: #1035326

[{'created': '2013-10-24 18:07:09.000000000', 'message': 'Adopt 0.1.8 as iso8601 minimum version

In the images api, we depend on iso8601 to parse some dates and times.
Recently, since version 0.1.4, python-iso8601 added support for a few
more formats, and we finally got some other issues nailed down by 0.1.8.
If end user switch from 0.1.8 back to 0.1.4 in the deployment, the image
api will lose support for certain datetime formats like YYYY-MM-DD
(where the time part is assumed to be all zeros). This obviously creates
a compatibility concern.

We were resolved to make glance compatible with both iso 0.1.4 and
0.1.8, but it appears that to do so requires essentially reimplementing
a large swath of iso8601 0.1.8 in glance itself.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Adopt 0.1.8 as iso8601 minimum version

In the images api, we depend on iso8601 to parse some dates and times.
Recently, since version 0.1.4, python-iso8601 added support for a few
more formats, and we finally got some other issues nailed down by 0.1.8.
If end user switch from 0.1.8 back to 0.1.4 in the deployment, the image
api will lose support for certain datetime formats like YYYY-MM-DD
(where the time part is assumed to be all zeros). This obviously creates
a compatibility concern.

We were resolved to make glance compatible with both iso 0.1.4 and
0.1.8, but it appears that to do so requires essentially reimplementing
a large swath of iso8601 0.1.8 in glance itself.

Fixes bug: 1242501

Change-Id: Iece0116d3c412216251e2d7fbffe10bfe2c1c789
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add newline to openstack-common.conf

When the module name gets replaced, the result has no newline at the end
of the file.  The first time you go change the file, you get an extra
changed line adding a newline.  Avoid this by adding an extra newline to
this file.

Change-Id: Iac2a1cbd183920abb14815a6f3a6eb8de7d80fd6

commit_message:
Configure nova-network database access on debian/ubuntu

The database configuration disappeared from the debian/ubuntu
installation guide. Add the configuration bits in nova.conf, as done for
other distributions.

Change-Id: I7f7c754c7ff8d6898149507b49efd5a9d51e7ef0
Closes-Bug: #1244216
Backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit c308a59cffd8a453c0b566686689556dcf68c90d)

commit_message:
Fixes NTP advices

Previously, the install-guide told about using the "ntpdate"
client in a cron job to update the time, which is a bad
advise. Also, it didn't tell how to install ntpdate either.
Using the ntp daemon is much better. This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: I6f624cf89d558bffcaee724e13274466a8fd3e2b
backport: havana

commit_message:
Fix FROM_PACKAGE checks for novnc and spice

The logic for installing novnc and spice from packages is broken,
which makes it impossible to install from git, which makes bug
1248923 more serious.

Change-Id: I9ae722a5470a16555bca9018da342485f6d3e896
Related-Bug: 1248923

commit_message:
Temporary disabling tests to update global-requirement

Currently, gate tests is preventing from updating the trove-client
version in global requirements and horizon due to chicken and egg
issue. By skipping these tests, the patch in global-requirement and
horizon can merge,

Once these patches merge, this fix will be reverted and the tests
will be enabled.

Fixes bug #1250202

Change-Id: I8f4e08b23fb37905c41bf34b58e9eb44b6ff0948

commit_message:
Fix horizon config under Apache 2.4

Apache 2.4 now uses mod_authz_host for acces control. Horizon's
Apache config needs an update to allow access to its directory,
otherwise a 403 will be returned.
This change replaces a similar previous fixes done for Fedora 18
and Ubuntu 13.10, since this is an Apache version issue, not a
distro-specific one.

Change-Id: Iecc17600d8e1aae6a7b0929b1493d712c307616f
Closes-Bug: #1243075

commit_message:
DHCP agent scheduler support for BigSwitch plugin

Adds support for the Neutron DHCP agent scheduler to the BigSwitch
plugin to support multiple neutron DHCP agents.

Implements: blueprint bsn-dhcp-agent-scheduler
Change-Id: I629ce73c0b97c2409b37afb85639282a116560b7

heatclient is failing if os-auth-token (OS_AUTH_TOKEN) is
provided. With this change, user can provide either auth token

Closes Bug: #1248265

commit_message:
heatclient is not working with os-auth-token

heatclient is failing if os-auth-token (OS_AUTH_TOKEN) is
provided. With this change, user can provide either auth token
or password with heatclient command line tool (heat).

Closes Bug: #1248265

Change-Id: I22b6af351dd3a371443f432b04785c706eff8325

on an existing subnet without replacement. Documentation
is limited on what properties are updatable, so discovery
was manual.

Change-Id: Ia585d1b7d24900f2789f2127a76dd272aa7fb850
'}]
commit_message:
Implement update for neutron subnet resources

This change allows any updatable properties to be updated
on an existing subnet without replacement. Documentation
is limited on what properties are updatable, so discovery
was manual.

Change-Id: Ia585d1b7d24900f2789f2127a76dd272aa7fb850

commit_message:
Resources for Rackspace Auto Scale

This introduces Rackspace::AutoScale::Group, ScalingPolicy,
and WebHook resources, to support the Rackspace Auto Scale
product.

Change-Id: I38b8f368d833b7475f260b8eb7afcc3a2a3770e7

commit_message:
Implement OS::Neutron::SecurityGroup

Some notes on the implementation:
* There is a single list of rules, with the 'direction'
  attribute denoting whether ingress or egress (ingress is the default)
* All attributes are updatable without resource replacement using
  prepare_update_properties.
* Rules update is implemented by:
  * deleting all rules
  * restoring default egress rules which allow all egress
  * adding new rules
* The remote_mode attribute allows switching from remote_ip_prefix
  to remote_group_id based associations
* As documented in the remote_group_id property, a rule can establish
  a self-reference to its own security group by specifying
  remote_mode: remote_group_id and not specifying any value for
  remote_group_id

Implements blueprint native-neutron-securitygroup
Partial-Bug: #1206313
Partial-Bug: #1243686

Change-Id: Id240fe02b5b85d7b11f48411a58e98d2d575c9a0

This change allows any updatable properties to be updated

commit_message:
Implement update for neutron network resources

This change allows any updatable properties to be updated
on an existing network without replacement. Documentation
is limited on what properties are updatable, so discovery
was manual.

The method prepare_update_properties can be used by other
neutron resources to implement their updates.

Change-Id: Ib128123544c4a62b4ba672203c1a81cf082a8847

commit_message:
change return value of validate_* functions in api_validator.py

From the function name of validate_*, it shall return True/False.
Some functions of validate_* follow this rule, while some others
are not.

Change-Id: I9cb925de2931b98fc4f1e6c85ae35e393209bd82

when at the DEBUG log level.  Default it to WARN to suppress that.

commit_message:
Default iso8601 logging to WARN

iso8601 logs a bunch of stuff we're probably not interested in
when at the DEBUG log level.  Default it to WARN to suppress that.

Change-Id: I0736fd62190fd0b3b26133916f8b3d4d9f0499c2

commit_message:
Refactor ISCSI driver to use Brick

This patch is a follow up to
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41528
This refactors the kvm libvirt iSCSI
volume driver to use Brick's
ISCSIConnector for volume attach/detaches.

blueprint refactor-iscsi-fc-brick

Change-Id: Ib1e574108d225326fff43c571ba8820d0d27b5a9

[{'created': '2013-11-11 11:44:24.000000000', 'message': 'Remove confusing comment and code for LBaaS

The comment "the driver is optional" is inconsistent with what actually
done. And "vif_driver = None" after raising an exception makes no sense.
So this patch removes these lines.

Change-Id: I7f3d5b6df61037307e952a478f47c59485601847
'}]
commit_message:
Remove confusing comment and code for LBaaS

The comment "the driver is optional" is inconsistent with what actually
done. And "vif_driver = None" after raising an exception makes no sense.
So this patch removes these lines.

Change-Id: I7f3d5b6df61037307e952a478f47c59485601847

commit_message:
Fix OLE error for HyperV

When run live-migration on HyperV, an OLE error
will occur. This is because we use wrong WQL
sentence when we try to query table
'Msvm_ResourceAllocationSettingData'.

This commit fixes the wrong WQL sentence.

Closes-Bug: #1246592

Change-Id: Iabb4096002a5be1fb930b077fbf5ef734893c258

commit_message:
Make scheduler disk_filter take swap into account

The disk_filter, which makes sure a node has enough disk space for an
instance doesn't take the swap partition into account, but swap takes up
disk space so it should.

Change-Id: I0779dcf0f1cd60017b5b49ca38c0a15b23d802d7
Closes-Bug: #1239009

Making the message only consist of primitive types
before sending it by qpid.

Fixes bug 1242734

commit_message:
fix lockutils.lock() to make it thread-safe

lockutils.lock() is currenctly safe when used with greenthreads, but it is not
safe when used with classic threads. This change uses a lock to protect
_semaphores dictionary.

Change-Id: Ia18e6e9f9a1353640729ac57d7225c660159cd55
Closes-Bug: 1065529

commit_message:
Adjust import order according to PEP8 imports rule

This patch just adjust import order to follow PEP8 imports rule.
See http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#imports
Imports should be grouped in the following order:

    standard library imports
    related third party imports
    local application/library specific imports

Change-Id: I6d92e9eda72d83cbf940b7699268f884bd4045c1

commit_message:
Remove BUSYBOX variable from ramdisk-defaults

ramdisk-defaults file is sourced before chroot to an image being created
is executed. Busybox path should be set inside chroot instead.

Change-Id: Ic0e1d3093ca9d489dd96b14157e93b336cf0baee

it turns out there was a loophole in the global-requirements to
rule them all approach, because tempest runs under tox, and the
default devstack behavior is to reset the source trees after

commit_message:
don't UNDO_REQUIREMENTS after we update from g-r

it turns out there was a loophole in the global-requirements to
rule them all approach, because tempest runs under tox, and the
default devstack behavior is to reset the source trees after
global-requirements was used for setup.py develop, so that we
wouldn't be poluting people's working trees.

This meant that if tempest contained an incompatible requirement
from g-r, it could wedge the gate (which it did for stable/havana).

We've since introduced UNDO_REQUIREMENTS in devstack that lets us
control this reset. This change in the gate will ensure that we
don't reset tempest back to a state where it can wedge us.

Change-Id: I6fb14cef9d52a35569c2f0215267609cd6741337

commit_message:
added check for quantum enabled via attribute

attribute openstack.compute.network.service_type
exists ... so lets use it to ensure we don't end up
with both nova-network and quantum installed.

Change-Id: Ia528264c14f31d13c0f4634c6a6da59dfe18aa02

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-08 10:53:28.000000000', 'message': 'Make it easier to use external routers with metadata from dhcp namespace

The dhcp agent only pushes out the metadata static route when the subnet
is isolated, and it determines that by checking if the gateway_ip is not set.
This makes it tricky to use external routers and metadata from dhcp at the
same time.

This patch changes how the dhcp agent determines that the subnet is
isolated. It now considers it isolated if there is no Neutron router on it.
This makes it straightforward to use an external router on a provider
network and get the metadata from the dhcp namespace.

Change-Id: I0e29a2f058564c267176dab26da00f6ef579808b
Closes-Bug: 1236783
'}, {'created': '2013-10-08 13:37:11.000000000', 'message': 'Simplify using external routers and metadata

The dhcp agent only pushes out the metadata
static route when the subnet is isolated, and it
determines that by checking if the gateway_ip is
not set. This makes it tricky to use external
routers and metadata from dhcp at the same time.

This patch changes how the dhcp agent determines

commit_message:
Simplify using external routers and metadata

The dhcp agent only pushes out the metadata
static route when the subnet is isolated, and it
determines that by checking if the gateway_ip is
not set. This makes it tricky to use external
routers and metadata from dhcp at the same time.

This patch changes how the dhcp agent determines
that the subnet is isolated. It now considers it
isolated if there is no Neutron router on it.
This makes it straightforward to use an external
router on a provider network and get the
metadata from the dhcp namespace.

Change-Id: I0e29a2f058564c267176dab26da00f6ef579808b
Closes-Bug: 1236783

commit_message:
Presents color contrast in resource usage charts

This makes use of d3.scale.category10() to allocate colors to per tenant
trend lines as opposed to d3.scale.category20().
This makes it easy to distinguish the color rendered for each new tenant as
d3.scale.category10() is a more contrasty.

Closes-Bug: #1243747

Change-Id: I6ac2bcd4fa831944dfb10944eb620d333e1f3644

commit_message:
Call baselineCPU for full feature list

Since the libvirt API getCapabilities doesn't return a full list of CPU features we need
to call the libvirt API baselineCPU with the new flag VIR_CONNECT_BASELINE_CPU_EXPAND_FEATURES
to get all features.

Since the flag is new this code checks for its existence before calling baselineCPU.

Also, due to some rather stringent input checking on libvirt's part, just calling
baselineCPU with the output from getCapabilities doesn't work, you have to extract
just the <cpu> stanza from the XML returned by getCapabilities.

Add unit test to make sure that the current verion of libvirt works (although
it will hide some features) and the new version of libvirt will correctly
return all features.

Fixes bug 1217630

Change-Id: I266bacb7e0c79d9c5b13ff163f01d14cad9ab57b

[{'created': '2013-11-05 19:26:07.000000000', 'message': "Document default log location in config files

It's not immediately obvious where log output will go if the 'log_file' and
'use_syslog' directives are either missing or commented out.  This patch updates
the documentation in the config files to mention the stdout default.  This
should help remove any confusion when configuring logging for glance.

Change-Id: I36f2a9d30bdee1949e60f413b7f181631c564ed5
Closes-Bug: #1248292

commit_message:
Document default log location in config files

It's not immediately obvious where log output will go if the 'log_file' and
'use_syslog' directives are either missing or commented out.  This patch updates
the documentation in the config files to mention the stdout default.  This
should help remove any confusion when configuring logging for glance.

Change-Id: I36f2a9d30bdee1949e60f413b7f181631c564ed5
Closes-Bug: #1248292

Currently, due to the way that instances are being retrieved by the
findall() function, an administrator can do a list, etc. with the
--all_tenants option and see other tenants' instances.  If the

with a 'No server with a name or ID of <name> exists.' error.

only resources that the user has access to are returned.

commit_message:
Enable del of other tenant's instance by name

Currently, due to the way that instances are being retrieved by the
findall() function, an administrator can do a list, etc. with the
--all_tenants option and see other tenants' instances.  If the
admin then tries to delete the another tenants' instance by name, it fails
with a 'No server with a name or ID of <name> exists.' error.

The solution to this is to change the call to the list() function in
findall() to set the all_tenants search option to 1.  This causes the
admin to get a list of all the instances that they have access to back
when the search is done instead of just a list of their resources.  The
delete by name is then possible.  The server takes care of ensuring that
only resources that the user has access to are returned.

This will enable delete by name for all resources that use the find_instance
function.

closes-bug: 1247030
Change-Id: I13273009155bb5949a1ccf5837971d1f24a92cc4

Configure nova-network database access on debian/ubuntu

The database configuration disappeared from the debian/ubuntu
installation guide. Add the configuration bits in nova.conf, as done for
other distributions.

commit_message:
VMware vSphere Config extend port range to include up to 6105

Change upper range [6000] to [6105 (inclusive)]
Added the following note:
In addition to the default VNC port numbers (5900 to 6000)
specified in the above document, the following ports are also
used: 6101, 6102 and 6105.

Change-Id: Ie4e5be478fad2b1c93033f22bda8108a0be06206
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1249250
(cherry picked from commit f08d24accd39f91406ec3499aa4479a23fc92c5c)

subject: (WiP) Management API - Proof of Concept
messages:
[{'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2013-10-31 21:20:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2013-10-31 21:20:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Work In Progress'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-11-01 12:03:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Do not merge

(4 inline comments)

Thanks for sharing, interesting way to start the discussion on this feature.

I think this whole idea needs careful consideration, because you seem to be (ab)using the is_admin flag, in a way we've not previously considered.

The keystone admin role can have two meanings AFAIK, you can be added to the admin role globally, or you can be an admin of just a specific project/tenant, but this idea seems to assume that there's one-true-admin, and that they're always globally empowered with admin-ness.

Part of the problem is that we currently allow all access on a tenant-scoped basis, e.g if you're a user in a tenant, you can view all stacks in that tenant.

Perhaps what we need to move towards is a more granular model:
- Tenant users can only view and modify stacks they created
- Tenant admins can view and modify any stacks in the tenant
- Admins not scoped to a specific tenant have superpowers and can view/modify any stacks.

This however presents problems with our current concept for in-instance users (where we create a new keystone user to authenticate the in-instance requests) - we need to move eventually to a model (using trusts is the current plan) where all credentials related to the stack are directly related to the stack-owner.

Then you have the new v3 keystone concept of domains, which we currently have no support for at all.  It's complicated area, and IMO it's not as simple as just plugging in an admin API, everything should be handled via the same ReST API, and the request scope should be determined by the keystone user/project/role/domain.

Probably we need to look again at how e.g Nova handles this, and align with similar behavior."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-11-01 18:41:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
(WiP) Management API - Proof of Concept

This is an initial draft of what features related to the management-api
blueprint would look like.
- Add an endpoint for accessing all stacks from all tenants: this way an
  admin can quickly look for failing stacks across the system.

blueprint management-api

Change-Id: I4c3a77597457b636320129c9055a3ca1764fdebd

'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2013-10-29 07:27:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Christian,

Cheers for your attention to detail :)

I do have to note, however, that "citetitle" has a special semantic meaning in the markup, so it is the technically correct thing to use here.

There's also a practical value to using it - with this change when we cut the next release, we don't have to alter this file at all. By changing them to links, it means we have to edit this file to eg change trunk to 'icehouse'. It also complicates backports - so we'd need to make a separate version of this patch for the havana tree.

So, in general, where possible we try to avoid making these kinds of links.

Now, about the italics - we may be able to fix that by looking at how citetitle gets turned into html in the end - but I think that discussion is best had on the mailing list. Is that OK?'}, {'account_id': 2448, 'date': '2013-11-04 01:38:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
ExtraRoute: fix _get_extra_routes_by_router_id()

router_id filter wasn't properly applied to the query
so the func returned all extra routes of all routers.

Closes-Bug: #1248219
Change-Id: I77733ee7994c8fccbbc966ccabd83b8fe4def8d5

commit_message:
RackConnect compatibility for Cloud Servers

Make the Cloud Servers resource aware of the RackConnect automation.
The Cloud Servers resource should wait for the RackConnect automation to
complete before proceeding with the server configuration.  Additionally,
the server's public IP will have changed, so any previously-fetched
public IP needs to be forgotten.

Blueprint rackconnect

Change-Id: I61676ac821695431cdba0d9a7d3b2e009f6ca3e4

commit_message:
Create a guide for scaling out Heat API's

This documentation describes a guide for scaling out the ReST and
CFN API's based on a devstack installation. HAProxy is used as a load
balancer, redirecting calls from CLI to the several API's instances.

Change-Id: I6efe988ce970f2a3aa08f39050f85dc1621e6774
Closes-bug: #1072958

commit_message:
Change deprecated CLI arguments

According to keystoneclient/shell.py, --token and --endpoint (with
their accompanying ENV vars SERVICE_TOKEN and SERVICE_ENDPOINT)
were retained only for Essex compatibility and should have been
removed during Grizzly, replaced with --os-token (OS_SERVICE_TOKEN)
and  --os-endpoint (OS_SERVICE_ENDPOINT).

This patch updates a couple of doc references to the old options,
and the sample_data tool.

Change-Id: I87060764f40b1612e3a440c3406d094536af4c9c

commit_message:
Move powervm specific flags into a group

Like other hyprervisors, PowerVM driver need itself group in
configuration file. That is more readable. This patche moves powervm
specif flags into new section [powervm], and add deprecated names and
groups, we can continue use old names and groups.

Implements: blueprint powervm-use-specific-config-group

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia644688888215d351aa690458af20f88bbb87884

commit_message:
VMware vSphere Config extend port range to include up to 6105

Change upper range [6000] to [6105 (inclusive)]
Added the following note:
In addition to the default VNC port numbers (5900 to 6000)
specified in the above document, the following ports are also
used: 6101, 6102 and 6105.

Change-Id: Ie4e5be478fad2b1c93033f22bda8108a0be06206
backport: havana
Closes-Bug: #1249250

commit_message:
Extract fix_etc_hosts method

Extract the work arounds for the /etc/hosts setup on HP cloud.

Change-Id: I346f361b936b0cf1c09245f59efb61111f948b34

commit_message:
Set a floor on the python-memcache library

python-memcache prior to version 1.48 will leak memory due to always
caching cas ids (compare and set) and with nothing designed to clean
it up.  In 1.48 it was changed to require a boolean argument 'cache_cas'
on init to enable the cas id caching.  In the case of keystone, we rely
on the cache_cas argument and cas functionality.  Ideally, all uses of
memcache should use later than 1.47 to prevent the memory leaking of
cas id caching.

Change-Id: Ide780e30a8243cd5fcc693515ffd84dfea3a3467

commit_message:
Make test_show_host_detail work with multi host installation

Get the host detail only if the host is compute host
and run the tests for all the compute host not just
for the first one.

Change-Id: I1830e6071c09d1e751048d74bd828d0eeac282f8
Closes-Bug: #1230000

commit_message:
Reformat openstack-common.conf

Like we did in other projects, use the new 'module' option in
openstack-common.conf which is a multi-string option, allowing
each module name to be placed on a separate line.

This makes it much easier to review changes to the modules list.

Change-Id: I4ea846ffd6db4ff26f4fa0b698191f38ce192071

(1 inline comment)

I'm not sure about auto-generating stuff from their web-pages..

- The CFN template/resource interface is versioned, do we expect it to change regularly (if at all)?
- We already have manually created schema for most aws-compatible resources, which describe what the resources actually implement.
- I worry about the auto-generated schema getting out of sync with the code, e.g how does this know that a property is not implemented in the code?

Maybe we'd be better to have a "check_aws_properties.py", which could even be a gate test I guess, which verifies the existing resource schemas match the AWS docs?'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-10-30 22:35:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Gating on a tool which scrapes a third-party website seems like a bad idea ;)'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-10-30 22:38:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

How about making this tool output in yaml, and write a corresponding tool which outputs heat's AWS schemas as yaml.

This would be more diff friendly, and we can periodically run both and manually analyse the diff"}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-10-30 23:05:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

So my initial view to doing this is we don't have a lot of view on what aws are up to, when they add properties/features to their resources. So I wanted to make something that would make this easier.

Something like:
run a script and it tells you what properties we are missing
we can then manually add/edit the tool's changes.

totally agree: we don't want to ever gate on a website that could change at any time (format/content).

At this point, this script is at the point of "hey guys look we can mechanically parse aws's properties and do *something*".'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2013-11-01 00:07:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Remove 'basestring' from objects utils

'basestring' type is not compatible with Python 3,
type from six library used. Also allows unicode
literals instead of str().

Change-Id: I2a8e9e3b36d58146386eaa700dba0227faed896e

commit_message:
Don't use deprecated module commands

The commands module was deprecated since version 2.6 and it has been
removed in Python 3. Use the subprocess module instead.
See http://docs.python.org/2/library/commands#module-commands

Closes-Bug: #1248216
Change-Id: I16d6baa77637f84b878df3ee6f964ddb9446d7bf

commit_message:
Added some more vagrant testing steps

Also added `$` to front of all sample shell commands.
* Helps ensure user knows it is a command to be run from CLI
* Also discourages bulk copy/paste running of the commands directly from example ( bad practice! )

Change-Id: I8c69874808756305c93b4d778c72772603441ad0

commit_message:
Quota value shouldn't be set less than in-use.

The data of how many resource in-use will be deleted when call the delete
quota api.Then you can update the quota to a value which less than in-use and
reserve.It's not correct.

The patch fix the bug.

Closes-bug: #1246668
Change-Id: I66262ff5d04c4677eeca77a56d664de6e548064b

commit_message:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack

When creating an RBD volume, various command line options can be specified;
two of these relate to data striping and are stripe_count and stripe_unit.

stripe_count: specifies the number of objects to stripe over before looping
back to the first object.
stripe_unit: specifies the stripe unit size in bytes

When the RBD driver is in use and 'Create Volume' is selected, switchable
RBD stripe count and stripe unit fields are added to volumes/forms.py when
the user selects a previously created volume type; the latter is implemented in Cinder.

Entered values (or defaults if none entered) are then passed to the cinder.volume_create

api/cinder.py modified to receive stripe parameters and subsequently
pass these to following method calls.

This implementation requires:
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (python-cinderclient)
Adding RBD data striping capabilities to OpenStack (Cinder)

blueprint rbd-stripe-parameters

Change-Id: Ia28fa584900e422da68cd7d7cf4179fdee204220

[{'created': '2013-07-22 14:41:47.000000000', 'message': "Whole Host Allocation - Pcloud framework

Work In Progress

This change introduces the basic framework for creating and managing
pclouds (private clouds), which can be used by projects to work with a
dedicated pool of hosts.   Unlike existing tenant isolation filters which
have to be configured by the cloud provider, pclouds are directly accessible
to users (subject to quotas and authorization of course)

Pclouds are implemented as a wrapper on top of host aggregates.

At this stage this is fully working code, but still needs more work on
unit tests.   It's being posted as WIP to allow some of the other dependant
changes to progress, and to collect comments on the overall approach.

Other changes will build on this to provide:
-	Quota Handling for pclouds
-	Scheduler Filter for pclouds
-	Host Allocation / Deallocation

Partly implements blueprint:  whole-host-allocation

Change-Id: I00af2dbdcd61a3008b279eaa556a04be0103b0c0

commit_message:
Whole Host Allocation - Pcloud framework

Work In Progress

This change introduces the basic framework for creating and managing
pclouds (private clouds), which can be used by projects to work with a
dedicated pool of hosts.   Unlike existing tenant isolation filters which
have to be configured by the cloud provider, pclouds are directly accessible
to users (subject to quotas and authorization of course)

Pclouds are implemented as a wrapper on top of host aggregates and exploit
other aggregate based features such as the AggregateCoreFilter and
AggregateRamFilter.

Hosts are allocated from host-flavors, which has its own management
API extension.

A Scheduler filter to allow authorised tenants to schedule into a Pcloud
is included.

This version includes the capability to allocate hosts into a Pcloud

For a full description of the design and examples of using via the
Nova client refer to these wiki pages:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/WholeHostAllocation
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/WholeHostAllocation-pcloud-example

At this stage this is fully working code, but still needs more work on
unit tests.   It's being posted as WIP to allow some of the other dependant
changes to progress, and to collect comments on the overall approach.

ToDo:
- Add unit tests
- Add v3 API
- Convert to Aggregate Objects

Other changes will build on this to provide:
-	Quota Handling for pclouds

Partly implements blueprint:  whole-host-allocation

Change-Id: I00af2dbdcd61a3008b279eaa556a04be0103b0c0

commit_message:
Get StringIO from io module for Py3 compatibility

The StringIO module is gone in Python 3, and the io module has been the
place to get StringIO from since it's creation in 3.0 and its backport
to 2.6. This change also adjusts two former StringIO usages to
BytesIO where appropriate for working with byte strings.

Change-Id: I62ca3bdf1c0a67e57bb15f572753295dcdb9f012

commit_message:
Use six.moves for Python 2 & 3 httplib imports.

This adds six to the requirements.txt file in order to make
some HTTP-related imports work across Python 2's httplib and Python 3's
http.client modules. Tests were updated, including one change to the
location of HTTPConnection - moving it from being accessed where it was
imported rather than its canonical location inside of
six.moves.http_client.

Change-Id: I3106599ed8a7cae4c9e9c61671ff313b2c6e58f1

commit_message:
Fix http_connect_raw for IPv6 support

Passing ipaddr&port as a colon seperated tuple is ambiguous in
IPv6 context. This patch sends 'ipaddr' and 'port' seperately.

Fixes bug 1244399

Change-Id: Ie096b82042e8acbefc091b71e812fe7a8bb9844e

commit_message:
Add rbd image download plug-in to handle ceph RBD locations

Nova downloads images through GlanceImageService. GlanceImageService
tries through the set of download plug-ins first, and if not successful,
it will download the image from glance itself.

In the current versions of nova, only 'file' and 'filesystem' based
location handlers are present. This feature will add 'rbd' based
location handler plug-in.

blueprint image-download-rbd-location

Change-Id: I1a4786447730eb9e98f92beaf5b9b350d7eb62e4

commit_message:
Returning the json body after a stack-create or stack-update

This allows the downstream service access to the data coming
back from the REST API, primarily the stack id.

implements blueprint return-id-on-stack-create

Change-Id: I24db9c28fca1f50f5ef1452679f444095d22d103

commit_message:
chef-zero and berkshelf plugins conflict on json gem version, change order

vagrant-chef-zero depends on the json 1.7.7 gem, vagrant-berkshelf will bring in
a newer version if it installs first, breaking vagrant-chef-zero. This needs to
get fixed upstream too.

Change-Id: I7f9d40b6b759a33c66dbab8dc62261cc54788e9e

commit_message:
Introduction of ceph::init, ceph::params

This is meant as a very minimal start in building ceph::init and
ceph::params. With ceph::repo, the module now allows, by itself,
Ceph's installation on the Debian family of operating systems.
System integration tests are not part of this commit and will come
later.

Change-Id: I0b5a71ccfe732ea53daa3f60199f5cca1024b9a2

I thought of it but...
Remember Heat is scaling because Ceilometer sent us an alarm
so there is the nova instance usage information for the number of instances that are used. Technically the template has not changed.

Saying all that...
The autoscaling group is now implemented as nested stack and
when we group.adjust() we just update the underlying stack, which means you will get an update usage message for that stack.'}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2013-10-24 09:24:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

Thanks for your feedback Angus.

re 
"I thought of it but... Remember Heat is scaling because Ceilometer sent us an alarm so there is the nova instance usage information for the number of instances that are used. Technically the template has not changed."

So I don't know how to retrieve the number of instances in an ASG via the ceilometer API ? may by using the groupby API ?

re
"Saying all that... The autoscaling group is now implemented as nested stack and when we group.adjust() we just update the underlying stack, which means you will get an update usage message for that stack."

yeah, I thought of the update notification for the nested stack (ASG), but the information are not sufficient IMHO (not directly available). I would like to have direct informations like 'instance(s) is/are added to this ASgroupId of this stack", 'instance(s) is/are removed from this ASgroupId of this stack' and have 'the list of instances uuid or IP of the ASG' for each AS notifications.

and idealy send these notifs when the autoscaling occurs really, not when alarm is triggered by ceilo because the "adjustement" may be aborted due to the cooldown mechanism.'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-10-25 02:07:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Send usage notifications on major stack events

These notifications can then be used for usage/billing/alarming purposes.

Some of the base fields are based on the existing nova fields:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/SystemUsageData

This patch just has the minimum fields needed we can add more as users
ask.

We can also add more notifications as we need:
- automated actions (autoscaling, restart)
- time based .exists notifications

implements blueprint send-notification
Change-Id: I63ad5402037799842643eb642af15b54ef8d7483

commit_message:
Check that the epel repo exists before adding it

The epel repo that contains cloud-init and other packages needed for the
rackspace resource does not always exists. The setup script will fail if
you try to import the repo when it exists because of running the script
with set -e.

Change-Id: If1f912c2e7cbe3ccd58e10d0ea2e1e07b2114b48

commit_message:
Updating the trove-client dependency

When trying to update the trove client in the global-requirement,
tempest tests are failing due to backward compatibility break in
horizon. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/52137/

commit_message:
Move docker specific options into a group.

There is only one example, but we're moving all hypervisor specific
options into groups.

DocImpact: rename docker_registry_default_port to
registry_default_port in the docker group.

Implements blueprint: docker-opts-group

Change-Id: Ic653e8a610876c40a715bff1ec48173d3bdb212e

commit_message:
enable novnc and xvpvnc

This enables novnc and xvpvnc. There will be tempest tests to test
vnc console API of nova.

Change-Id: I363f8ac376b6ea30ebeb89f7d7fd32f035b232f6

In the summit session of "Using Pecan/WSME for Nova V3 API" yesterday, we have gotten a consensus using Pecan(without WSME) for Nova v3 API.

If moving Pecan, some API URLs should be changed. for example, we cannot use "v3/os-agents" as API URL due to Pecan specification.

After merging this patch set, should we skip the tempest tests related to these APIs before Nova's change?

I think the coverage of Nova v3 API is important, and it is better to start Tempest tests soon. I'd like to just confirm the implementation way for next works.'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-08 08:36:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 36: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

commit_message:
port test_images and test_server_actions into v3 part2

this ports test_images and server_action tests into v3 and
add a BaseComputeV3Test to avoid that nova v3 tests
call nova v2 url by mistake.

In nova v3 API there is no image API. So use glance
directly in test_images and change create_image to use
servers_client instead of images_client in BaseComputeTest,
as it's server's action.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I0371abbdce092d566c312ea73c563d817b37e226

commit_message:
port test_images and test_server_actions into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files. There
is no image api in nova v3 api, so the images_client won't be ported
into v3 test. We will use glance directly.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I058407afb7bba4d55c619db27f59a91a46cbc6cf
